"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449258","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-10","<p>The region has some of the most iconic tourist attractions in the UK and tourism is an essential part of the local economy. We want to ensure that our tourism businesses have as much support as possible as they recover from the recent floods. Some tourism businesses in flood affected areas have reported a drop in bookings of up to 60%.</p><p>That is why a new £1m PR campaign was launched by the Prime Minister in Cumbria, on the 28th January, to support businesses ready to receive visitors, and this is part of a wider package of immediate measures to help the area.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449258/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-10T17:47:48.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449258/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449258/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-01","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the tourist industry in Cumbria of recent flooding and severe weather.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449259","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Department does not have an estimate of the cost to businesses in Cumbria as a result of recent flooding. We expect at least 2,000 businesses to have been impacted by the flooding, based on reports from local partners, with many more affected as a result of secondary issues such as damage to important infrastructure such as the A591.</p><p> </p><p>We know that getting timely support in place is really important and that is why we moved quickly, with Cumbria County Council and Cumbria Local Enterprise Partnership, to put in place a business recovery scheme. Cumbria have already received £2.6 million of funding to begin paying to businesses to help them recover and as more applications are made by businesses we’ll provide additional funding from the £11m we have made available to support business recovery following this winter’s flooding.</p><p> </p><p>Flooded businesses also benefit from businesses rates relief and can also apply for up to £5,000 to make sure that property repairs include greater resilience to any future flooding.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449259/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:51:52.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449259/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449259/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-01","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to businesses in Cumbria of recent flooding and severe weather.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449260","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with minimum wage legislation and effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it.</p><p> </p><p>Employers who pay workers less than the minimum wage not only have to pay arrears of wages at current minimum wage rates but also face financial penalties of up to £20,000 per underpaid worker. A further increase in penalties will come into force in April 2016 and will increase the penalty percentage from 100% to 200% of the underpayments owed to each worker, up to the existing maximum.</p><p> </p><p>Work on the campaign continues so I refer the honourable member to the answer provided at UIN 8859.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449260/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:55:48.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449260/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449260/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number of employers who self-reported their non-compliance with the national minimum wage as a result of the Government's recent campaign on their policy.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","25177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449261","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>There is no requirement for local councils to request such flexibility. However, to ensure that local taxpayers can see and compare the level of funding and support, including facility time, given to unions, the Government now requires councils to annually publish this information on their websites.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449261/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:03:52.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449261/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449261/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Local Government: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities have requested (a) the removal of and (b) increased flexibility for trades union facilitation time since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","25251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449262","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449262/answer","25210 FINAL.pdf","25210 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Main Causes of Death","UKSA Letter to Member - Main Causes of Death",,"2016-02-04T14:15:51.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449262/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449262/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-01","Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the main causes of death are for (a) men and (b) women aged (i) five to 19 and (ii) 20 to 34 in England.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","25210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449263","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Civil Service has a significant presence across the UK and we are considering how new government hubs, in strategic locations across the country, will help to make sure that we have an efficient and effective Civil Service at the same time as we consolidate the government estate. Currently, 18.1% of civil servants are based in London.</p><p>Any proposed relocation is done based on operational need.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449263/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-10T13:48:44.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449263/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449263/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-01","Civil Servants: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what his policy is on rebalancing the Civil Service between London and the regions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449264","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-03","<p>Details of Ministers' meetings with external organisations are published on a quarterly basis and can be found on Gov.uk.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449264/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T12:27:00.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449264/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449264/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-01","Cabinet Office: Soft Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions (a) the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and (b) the Paymaster General have had with representatives of (i) the Food and Drink Federation, (ii) Coca-Cola, (iii) PepsiCo and (iv) the British Soft Drinks Association.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","24997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449265","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>67% of the Senior Civil Service is based in London.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449265/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T09:31:45.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449265/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449265/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-01","Senior Civil Servants: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of people in the Senior Civil Service are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449266","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Severe Weather Helpline was originally set up in February 2014. Details of the calls received and the average time taken to answer a call since this helpline was set up are shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Severe Weather Helpline</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tax Year</p></td><td><p>Calls received</p></td><td><p>Average time taken to answer call</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13-14</p></td><td><p>660</p></td><td><p>8 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14-15</p></td><td><p>874</p></td><td><p>14 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15-16*</p></td><td><p>1,339</p></td><td><p>32 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>2,873</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*until 31/01/16</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs are unable to provide information on the number of full-time equivalent staff on the flooding helpline as this is not held.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449266/answer",,,,,"25122","2016-02-09T16:57:05.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449266/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449266/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many telephone calls were made to HM Revenue and Customs' flooding tax helpline in each of the last five years; and what the average amount of time taken to answer a telephone call to that line was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","24998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449267","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>This information is not held by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).</p><p> </p><p>HMRC handles around 50 million telephone calls annually and regularly publishes general performance reports at Gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449267/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T17:01:43.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449267/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449267/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many telephone calls HM Revenue and Customs has received from (a) small businesses, (b) medium-sized businesses and (c) large businesses in each of the last five years; and what the average time taken to answer telephone calls from each such category of business was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","24999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449268","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not disclose details of its work on the affairs of particular taxpayers.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s Large Business directorate now deploys 2,600 staff – over 600 more than when it was formed in April 2014.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449268/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:21:17.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449268/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449268/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Google: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff at which grades were involved in the recent investigation into Google's tax arrangements.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449269","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Diverted Profits Tax is designed to counter contrived tax arrangements used by some multinationals to shift their profits to other countries. It is deliberately set at a higher rate than corporation tax, so it acts as a deterrent and encourages more companies to pay corporation tax.</p><p> </p><p>To date no companies have been issued with a charging notice under section 95 Finance Act 2015 which brings diverted profits tax into charge. However, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) received notifications from eleven companies under section 92 in relation to section 86 Finance Act 2015 over the period 1 April 2015 to 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p>For companies with accounting periods ending on or before 31 March 2016 the notification period is six months from the end of that period. HMRC is not able to disclose details of notifications relating to sections 80 and 81 of the Finance Act 2015 due to its duty to protect taxpayer confidentiality.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449269/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-29T16:58:20.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449269/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449269/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many companies have been subject to a diverted profits charge since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449270","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>British Business Bank’s investment in Funding Circle is one of a portfolio of investments managed by the commercial arm of the bank – British Business Bank Investments Ltd. To date, £60m has been committed to Funding Circle, an amount which has supported over 7,000 businesses. The investment contributes a financial return in line with the performance of the wider portfolio.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449270/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T15:58:07.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449270/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449270/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-01","British Business Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the returns to the public purse of British Business Bank investments in Funding Circle.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","25042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449271","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The information is not held in the form requested. The estimated amounts of Patent Box relief can be found at the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/487119/Dec15_expenditure_reliefs_Final.xlsx.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/487119/Dec15_expenditure_reliefs_Final.xlsx.pdf</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449271/answer",,,,,"25091 ; 25093 ; 25094 ; 25095","2016-02-09T17:00:50.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449271/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449271/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Patents: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value is of the tax relief granted through the patent box in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","25092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449272","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>I refer the right honourable gentleman to the answer I gave on 3 February [22572, 22658 &amp;22668].</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449272/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:12:43.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449272/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449272/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the size was of Concentrix's backlog of tax credit claims in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","25067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449273","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses two Google operating systems.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC uses the Android Operating system in a small number of mobile phone handsets, equating to less than 4% of its mobile phone estate. This Operating System was first used in 2012 in a small number of handsets, before being rolled out more widely in 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC also uses the Google Chrome Operating System in our video conference units. The Department started using this operating system for its video conferencing facilities in March 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449273/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:25:46.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449273/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449273/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what Google operating systems are used by HM Revenue and Customs; and when use of those systems commenced.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449274","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government has made no assessment of the effect of mineral rights on mortgage lending.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449274/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:45:02.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449274/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449274/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of mineral rights on mortgage lending.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","25068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449275","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs have had no discussions with Google on systems for collection of tax in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on whether other parts of Government have had discussions with Google.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449275/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:19:52.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449275/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449275/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) other parts of the Government have had with Google on systems for collection of tax in the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449276","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is legally prohibited from discussing the tax affairs of identifiable businesses.</p><p> </p><p>Section 18 of the Commissioners for Revenue &amp; Customs Act 2005 imposes a duty of confidentiality upon officers of HMRC which means they are unable to disclose information which relates to functions of HMRC. This includes any specific action taken in response to information provided.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449276/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:26:59.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449276/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449276/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","ClearSprings Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether (a) Clearsprings (Management) Ltd and (b) Clearsprings (Ready Homes) Ltd are under investigation by HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449277","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>Criminal investigation by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is part of a number of compliance interventions. Criminal investigation and prosecution act as a deterrent and support wider and more cost effective compliance interventions.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC takes cases to court when litigation is necessary. Since April 2013, HMRC has won 80%. Over £1.37 billion tax was protected by litigation against large business avoidance in that period.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449277/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:13:47.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449277/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449277/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many prosecutions have arisen from investigations undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs Large Business Service in each of the last three years; and what the (a) category of taxes involved in and (b) result was of each such prosecution.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449278","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>Data could be obtained at disproportionate cost showing the volume of cases withdrawn.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449278/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:50:57.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449278/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449278/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2016 to Question 22971, if he will require HM Revenue and Customs to collect data on the (a) the number of tax recipients who have their credits erroneously withdrawn and (b) reasons given for those withdrawals.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","25200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449279","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold this information.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449279/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:51:54.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449279/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449279/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many phone calls were made to HM Revenue and Customs' High Net Worth Unit in each of the last five years; and what the average amount of time taken was to answer a phone call to that unit in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","25191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449280","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government has received a number of representations to help repair the A591 damaged by the recent Storms, including a request for assistance from Cumbria County Council, the local highway authority, who is ultimately responsible for the management and maintenance of the road.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Transport announced on 27 December 2015 the Department for Transport would be providing £40 million to help rebuild vital local highway infrastructure in Cumbria and Lancashire damaged by the recent storms, including the damaged section of the A591. This announcement built on the government’s earlier provision of up to £2 million in the initial aftermath of the severe wet weather to enable Cumbria and Lancashire authorities to carry out an initial assessment of what repairs were required to roads and bridges.</p><p> </p><p>A follow up announcement regarding the A591 was made on 14 January 2016 which highlighted that Highways England, along with their contractors, has been brought in to deliver a full and permanent reinstatement of the road as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Further information is in the following weblink: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-announces-plans-to-reopen-a591-in-cumbria-following-storm-desmond-and-eva" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-announces-plans-to-reopen-a591-in-cumbria-following-storm-desmond-and-eva</a></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449280/answer",,,,,"25169","2016-02-04T16:42:41.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449280/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449280/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","A591","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make funds available to expedite the process of reopening the A591 in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449281","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Severe Weather Helpline was originally set up in February 2014. Details of the calls received and the average time taken to answer a call since this helpline was set up are shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Severe Weather Helpline</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tax Year</p></td><td><p>Calls received</p></td><td><p>Average time taken to answer call</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13-14</p></td><td><p>660</p></td><td><p>8 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14-15</p></td><td><p>874</p></td><td><p>14 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15-16*</p></td><td><p>1,339</p></td><td><p>32 seconds</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>2,873</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*until 31/01/16</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs are unable to provide information on the number of full-time equivalent staff on the flooding helpline as this is not held.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449281/answer",,,,,"24998","2016-02-09T16:57:05.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449281/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449281/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many full-time equivalent staff were employed by HM Revenue and Customs' flooding tax helpline in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","25122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449282","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>Disputes with taxpayers of all types as to the right amount of tax that is due are a normal part of tax administration. There is huge variation in the nature of tax disputes depending on the complexity of the taxpayer’s behaviour, the amount and type of tax at stake and the transactions undertaken. Under its statutory powers, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) resolves most civil tax disputes by agreement and without resorting to litigation where the settlement secures the tax that HMRC believes is due under the law. If the right amount can’t be agreed, the dispute goes to litigation at the Tribunal. For any dispute, HMRC’s decision on how it should be resolved is taken by the final appropriate decision maker with appropriate management oversight. For the majority of cases this will constitute authorisation by a case worker’s line manager. However, the most significant and sensitive cases are considered by three Commissioners.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449282/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T17:05:50.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449282/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449282/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many commercial organisations have reached a negotiated settlement with HM Revenue and Customs on the amount of tax owed to the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","25132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449283","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>The independent Low Pay Commission will recommend future National Living Wage rates as well as continuing its current role in recommending National Minimum Wage rates.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449283/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T17:27:04.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449283/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449283/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-01","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make it his policy to include the new wage rate recommendations published annually by the Low Pay Commission in calculation of the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Joanna Cherry","Edinburgh South West","Joanna  Cherry","25140"
