"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449296","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government has received a number of representations to help repair the A591 damaged by the recent Storms, including a request for assistance from Cumbria County Council, the local highway authority, who is ultimately responsible for the management and maintenance of the road.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Transport announced on 27 December 2015 the Department for Transport would be providing £40 million to help rebuild vital local highway infrastructure in Cumbria and Lancashire damaged by the recent storms, including the damaged section of the A591. This announcement built on the government’s earlier provision of up to £2 million in the initial aftermath of the severe wet weather to enable Cumbria and Lancashire authorities to carry out an initial assessment of what repairs were required to roads and bridges.</p><p> </p><p>A follow up announcement regarding the A591 was made on 14 January 2016 which highlighted that Highways England, along with their contractors, has been brought in to deliver a full and permanent reinstatement of the road as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Further information is in the following weblink: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-announces-plans-to-reopen-a591-in-cumbria-following-storm-desmond-and-eva" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-announces-plans-to-reopen-a591-in-cumbria-following-storm-desmond-and-eva</a></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449296/answer",,,,,"25172","2016-02-04T16:42:41.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449296/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449296/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","A591","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many representations he has received on reopening the A591.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449297","Department of Health","false","2016-02-08","<p>We are informed by the Health and Social Care Information Centre that the information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449297/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T13:00:29.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449297/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449297/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-01","Home Care Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many home visits were provided to adult social care clients (a) in total and (b) per 1,000 of the population aged 65 and over in each English local authority in (i) 2009-10 and (ii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","24975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449298","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>Expenditure on adult social care, in 2010-11 (adjusted to real terms) and 2014-15 (the latest year for which figures are available), for each local authority in England, is attached.</p><p>It is not possible, from the data available, to dis-aggregate adult social care expenditure for the age range requested.</p><p>Due to differences in definition and changes to the responsibility of service provision between the NHS and local government, it is not possible to compare figures for 2010-11 with 2014-15. In particular, prior to the introduction of the Public Health Grant, elements of public health expenditure may have been classified as adult social care expenditure within the relevant statistical returns.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449298/answer","PQ 25011.xlsx","PQ 25011.xlsx","Table","Table",,"2016-02-04T16:25:25.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449298/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449298/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Social Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the change was in real terms expenditure on social care (a) overall and (b) per 1,000 head of population aged 65 or over in each local authority between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","25011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449299","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>Expenditure on children’s social care, in 2010-11 (adjusted to real terms) and 2014-15 (the latest year for which figures are available), for each local authority in England, is attached.</p><p>Data on children’s social care expenditure is not collected for the age range requested.</p><p>Due to differences in definition, it is not possible to compare figures for 2010-11 with 2014-15. In particular, elements of services to young people are now included within education expenditure.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449299/answer","PQ 25012.xlsx","PQ 25012.xlsx","Table","Table",,"2016-02-04T16:26:51.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449299/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449299/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Social Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the change in real terms spending on children's service (a) overall and (b) per 1,000 head of population aged 0 to 19 was in each local authority between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","25012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449300","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>The available information on homelessness decisions taken and acceptances for each region in England for each financial year from 2004/05 to 2014/15 is given in the attached table.</p><p>Information for other parts of the UK are a matter for the devolved Administrations.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449300/answer","Acceptances and Decisions ethnicity 200405.docx","Acceptances and Decisions ethnicity 200405.docx","Table","Table",,"2016-02-04T16:23:47.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449300/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449300/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Homelessness: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the change in the number of BME households who have (a) applied and (b) been accepted for homeless status was in each region and constituent nation of the UK between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","25013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449301","Home Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>On 1 April 2015, in line with wider public service pension reform, new career average pension arrangements were introduced for police officers and firefighters. These changes have put pension arrangements on a sustainable footing for the future, setting a fair balance of costs between public servants and other taxpayers, while continuing to provide good pensions for police officers and firefighters which reflect their roles.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449301/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:03:33.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449301/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449301/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-01","Emergency Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what safeguards are in place to ensure no shortfalls occur in future in the pensions of firefighters and police officers.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","24996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449302","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The information is not available.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449302/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T12:10:14.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449302/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449302/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Supported Housing: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the proportion of the actual cost of living in supported accommodation that will be met by discretionary housing payments in Warrington when housing benefit us capped at the rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","25058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449303","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The New Homes Bonus was introduced in 2011. To date the total New Homes Bonus payments allocated to Corby Borough Council is £3,135,997<strong>.</strong> The breakdown in years is in the table below</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>New Homes Bonus allocations to Corby Borough Council</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 1 (2011-2012)</p></td><td><p>£415,135</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 2 (2012-2013)</p></td><td><p>£651,254</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 3 (2013-2014)</p></td><td><p>£534,431</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 4 (2014-2015)</p></td><td><p>£542,088</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 5 (2015-2016)</p></td><td><p>£504,895</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 6 (2016-2017) - Provisional allocations</p></td><td><p>£488,194</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£3,135,997</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449303/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T13:20:05.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449303/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449303/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Housing: Corby","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much Corby Borough Council received under the New Homes Bonus in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","25080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449304","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him on 2 December 2015, PQ 18460.</p><p>At that time, Right to Buy campaign spend figures for October and November were provisional as the campaign was still running. Confirmed monthly expenditure from October to December 2015 is as follows:</p><p>October - £155,001<br>November - £171,066<br>December - £142,656</p><p>Figures for January 2016 are still be finalised so are not yet available.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449304/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:05:46.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449304/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449304/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Right to Buy Scheme: Publicity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department spent on advertising the Right to Buy scheme for council and housing association tenants in each month from October 2015 to January 2016.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","25008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449305","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-05","<p>The New Homes Bonus was introduced in 2011. To date the total New Homes Bonus payments allocated to Northamptonshire County Council is £4,737,550<strong>. </strong> The annual breakdown is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year 1<br>(2011-2012)</p></td><td><p>£647,233</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 2<br>(2012-2013)</p></td><td><p>£783,561</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 3<br>(2013-2014)</p></td><td><p>£674,225</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 4<br>(2014-2015)</p></td><td><p>£659,096</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 5<br>(2015-2016)</p></td><td><p>£931,180</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 6<br>(2016-2017) - provisional allocation</p></td><td><p>£1,042,255</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p><strong> £4,737,550 </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449305/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T13:18:39.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449305/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449305/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Housing: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much Northamptonshire County Council received under the New Homes Bonus in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","25030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449306","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-05","<p>The New Homes Bonus was introduced in 2011. To date the total New Homes Bonus payments allocated to East Northamptonshire District Council is £2,626,043<strong>. </strong> The annual breakdown is shown in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 1<br>(2011-2012)</p></td><td><p>£355,008</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 2<br>(2012-2013)</p></td><td><p>£ 551,047</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 3<br>(2013-2014)</p></td><td><p>£ 311,916</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 4<br>(2014-2015)</p></td><td><p>£306,847</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 5<br>(2015-2016)</p></td><td><p>£492,452</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Year 6<br>(2016-2017 - provisional allocation)</p></td><td><p>£608,774</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p><strong> £2,626,043 </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449306/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T13:20:13.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449306/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449306/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-01","Housing: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much East Northamptonshire Council received under the New Homes Bonus in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","25031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449307","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Heritage Lottery fund have allocated £13.9m to 58 projects in Northern Ireland to commemorate the First World War. The projects are spread across Northern Ireland and two are in South Antrim. I have asked the HLF to write to you with details of all the projects.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449307/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:01:18.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449307/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449307/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-01","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much of his Department's £13.9 million First World War commemoration funding will be provided to projects in Northern Ireland; and to which such projects that funding will be provided.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","25039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449308","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Since 2011, Sport England has invested £458,553 of National Lottery funding to upgrade and improve grassroots sports facilities in Coventry. The Government's recently published 'Sport Strategy' (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sporting-future-a-new-strategy-for-an-active-nation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sporting-future-a-new-strategy-for-an-active-nation</a>) provides a vision for future investment in sport, including increased funding for grass roots sports facilities. Sport England are now consulting on their own strategy to implement this.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England National Lottery investment, broken down by local authority area, is publicly available on Sport England’s website and can be found here: www.sportengland.org/funding/investments-weve-made.</p><p> </p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449308/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:32:45.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449308/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449308/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-01","Sports: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what funding was allocated to projects to support grassroots sports facilities in Coventry in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","25126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449309","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>A number of measures to improve the reliability of the Type 45 Power and Propulsion systems have been identified and the ongoing programme to implement these changes continues to deliver positive results, with the majority of work undertaken so far being at Her Majesty's Naval Base, Portsmouth.</p><p>In addition, and as part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, we are committed to improving system resilience by adding upgraded diesel generators to provide further electrical generation capacity. Alternative technical options and a variety of delivery models are currently being explored with several competing industrial partners. The total cost and timetable for implementing the diesel generator upgrade will be determined at the main investment decision. I am withholding details of our current time and cost estimates as premature disclosure of this information could prejudice the commercial interests of the Department.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449309/answer",,,,,"25149","2016-02-08T16:12:05.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449309/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449309/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when his Department plans for work to begin on rectifying electrical and propulsion faults on the Daring Class Type 45 Destroyer; which ships such rectification work will involve; and when his Department plans for such work to end for each such ship involved.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449310","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-04","<p>We are not providing support on the basis of faith or religion. In Iraq, our focus has been on the Iraqi security forces, including the Kurdish Peshmerga, to whom we have provided training in infantry skills and tactics to counter improvised explosive devices. We have also provided medical training. In Syria, we have delivered over £4 million of life-saving equipment to moderate opposition groups including communications, medical and logistics equipment, and protection against chemical weapons attacks.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449310/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:23:45.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449310/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449310/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department is providing to Christian militias in the fight against Daesh in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","25112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449311","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>The 2015 National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review identifies cyber security as a priority. We are actively monitoring cyber threats, and continually reviewing and adjusting our security measures. Defence and its people are prominent targets for criminals, foreign intelligence services and other malicious actors seeking to exploit personnel, disrupt business and operations, corrupt systems and steal information. This is not unique to the Ministry of Defence; other Government Departments, industry and business are also affected. The threats constantly changes in scope and complexity, and cyber security depends on a broad range of factors including human, technological and systematic. Our approach therefore spans technical, organisational, policy, procedural and physical measures, and also entails close collaboration with partner organisations across Government.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449311/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T13:20:59.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449311/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449311/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure cyber defence capabilities and preparedness match developing threats.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","25087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449312","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The figures for unauthorised entries to military bases include drones and air balloon flying at low altitude over military sites but do not include failed attempts at unauthorised access. None of these incidents resulted in any significant ramifications for Defence Security.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) treats all unauthorised entries very seriously. They are investigated to a level commensurate with their complexity and impact by Military Police, MOD Police or local constabulary.</p><p> </p><p>The locations of security incidents of this category recorded within the MOD for 2015 are set out below.</p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty’s Naval Base (HMNB) Portsmouth (three incidents)</p><p>HMNB Devonport</p><p>HMS TEMERAIRE, Portsmouth</p><p>Royal Marine Reserves Unit, Bristol</p><p>Priorswood Army Cadet Force Detachment, Taunton</p><p>Imjin Barracks, Gloucester</p><p>Denison Barracks, Hermitage</p><p>Caen Barracks, Hohne</p><p>Mansergh Barracks, Gutersloh</p><p>Invicta Park Barracks, Maidstone</p><p> </p><p>Imjin Barracks, Gloucester</p><p>Allenby Barracks Army Reserve Centre, Bovington</p><p>Gibraltar Barracks, Minley</p><p>Cherrytree Camp, Colchester</p><p>Cwmbran Army Reserve Centre, Cwmbran</p><p>Westward House Army Reserve Centre, Grimsby</p><p>Westdown Camp, Tilshead</p><p>Kinloss Barracks, Kinloss</p><p>Kendrew Barracks Cottesmore</p><p>Redford Cavalry Barracks, Edinburgh</p><p>Fox Barracks Army Reserve Centre, Chester</p><p>Gorleston Army Cadet Force Detachment, Gorleston-on-Sea</p><p>Livingstone Army Reserve Centre, Livingston</p><p>Stanley Barracks, Wareham</p><p>Normanby Army Cadet Force Detachment, Middlesbrough</p><p>Aliwal Barracks, Tidworth</p><p>Tamworth Army Cadet Force Detachment, Tamworth</p><p>Merville Barracks, Colchester</p><p>Canal Street Army Reserve Centre, Wigan</p><p>Batley Army Cadet Force Detachment, Batley</p><p>RAF Waddington</p><p>RAF Marham</p><p>RAF Uxbridge</p><p>RAF St Mawgan</p><p>RAF Brampton</p><p>RAF Lossiemouth</p><p>RAF Cosford</p><p>RAF Leeming (two incidents)</p><p>RAF Akrotiri</p><p>MOD Lyneham</p><p>DSTL Porton Down Range Area</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449312/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:22:04.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449312/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449312/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Military Bases: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 24141, at which military bases unauthorised entries were reported in 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449313","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>However all security incidents are passed for assessment and investigation with further action taken as appropriate. This may include investigation by Military Police, Ministry of Defence Police or local constabulary where necessary.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449313/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:22:59.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449313/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449313/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 24141, how many (a) unauthorised entries to military bases and (b) thefts or losses of classified material which were reported in 2015 led to further action after an initial security risk assessment.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449314","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>The apparent increase in incidents is attributed to security awareness programmes and a strengthened reporting regime. These have led to an increasing readiness to report even minor breaches and do not represent systematic failings in security protection.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449314/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:09:55.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449314/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449314/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 24141, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in the number of (a) unauthorised entries to military bases and (b) thefts or losses of classified material between 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449315","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>Other security breaches include incidents which represented a failure of a control but did not result in the loss of any information. Such breaches would be the contravention of security policy, damage, denial of service, malicious software and personal security.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449315/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:17:24.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449315/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449315/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 24141, what categories of security incident were classed as other security breach in that answer.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449316","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>A number of measures to improve the reliability of the Type 45 Power and Propulsion systems have been identified and the ongoing programme to implement these changes continues to deliver positive results. In addition, and as part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, we are committed to improving system resilience by adding upgraded diesel generators to provide further electrical generation capacity. Alternative technical options and a variety of delivery models are currently being explored with several competing industrial partners.</p><p>A number of early modifications were implemented under the Type 45 Destroyer Contract for Availability arrangement with BAE Systems at no additional cost to the Ministry of Defence. The total cost and timetable for implementing the diesel generator upgrade will be determined at the main investment decision. I am withholding details of our current time and cost estimates as premature disclosure of this information could prejudice the commercial interests of the Department.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449316/answer",,,,,"25238 ; 25240","2016-02-08T16:05:43.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449316/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449316/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what work will be required on each of the Daring Class Type 45 Destroyers in the fleet due to electrical and propulsion faults; and what estimate he has made of the cost of such work.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449317","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>A number of measures to improve the reliability of the Type 45 Power and Propulsion systems have been identified and the ongoing programme to implement these changes continues to deliver positive results, with the majority of work undertaken so far being at Her Majesty's Naval Base, Portsmouth.</p><p>In addition, and as part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, we are committed to improving system resilience by adding upgraded diesel generators to provide further electrical generation capacity. Alternative technical options and a variety of delivery models are currently being explored with several competing industrial partners. The total cost and timetable for implementing the diesel generator upgrade will be determined at the main investment decision. I am withholding details of our current time and cost estimates as premature disclosure of this information could prejudice the commercial interests of the Department.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449317/answer",,,,,"25148","2016-02-08T16:12:05.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449317/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449317/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, where his Department plans for work to take place on rectifying the electrical and propulsion faults on the Daring Class Type 45 Destroyers.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449318","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>A number of early modifications were implemented under the Type 45 Destroyer Contract for Availability arrangement with BAE Systems, at no additional cost to the Ministry of Defence (MOD). The initial work to prove the concept of upgrading the diesel generators was co-funded by BAE Systems and the MOD. Subject to main gate approval, the upgrade will be funded by the MOD.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449318/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:13:30.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449318/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449318/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department will pay out of the public purse for the cost of repairs to the electrical and propulsion systems on the Daring Class Type 45 Destroyers.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449319","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>Due to the specific requirements of Anti-Submarine Warfare operations and the availability of equipment on the open market, the Type 45 and Type 26 Global Combat Ship (T26 GCS) electrical and propulsion system architectures are fundamentally different; no major equipment will be common to both.</p><p>Lessons learned from the Type 45 programme and the in-service experience drawn from the Type 23 Anti-Submarine Warfare Frigates have all been applied to the T26 GCS electrical and propulsion system design.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449319/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:12:50.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449319/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449319/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Warships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which common electrical and propulsion systems are shared between the T26 Global Combat Ship and the Type 45 Destroyer.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449320","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>In the interests of National Security I am not prepared to release information concerning the type or nature of any failure or defect concerning our operational Units as to do so would allow deductions to be made as to their operational capability and effectiveness.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449320/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:43:58.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449320/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449320/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many times Daring Class Type 45 Destroyers underwent total electrical failure in the (a) Persian Gulf, (b) Strait of Hormuz, (c) Mediterranean Sea, (d) Indian Ocean and (e) North Atlantic Ocean.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449321","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Independent Power and Propulsion System Performance Review, dated March 2011, highlighted sixteen recommendations to improve the reliability of the Type 45 Destroyer's Power and Propulsion system. Fourteen of the recommendations have been completed across the class.</p><p>The remaining two recommendations, involving modifications to existing training procedures and documentation, have been incorporated into day to day business.</p><p>Implementation of these recommendations has directly contributed to an improvement in reliability.</p><p>All but one of the fourteen tasks were implemented under the Type 45 Destroyer Contract For Availability (CFA) arrangement with BAE Systems, at no additional cost to the Ministry of Defence.</p><p>The only task not covered under the CFA contract cost a total of £24,000 for the six Type 45 ships.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449321/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:21:01.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449321/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449321/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Warships: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on which Royal Navy ships were repairs carried out from March 2011 following the review of electrical and propulsion systems; and what the cost of those repairs was.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449322","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>The number of security incidents recorded within the Ministry of Defence in each of the years in question is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Unauthorised entries to Military Bases</p></td><td><p>Thefts or losses of classified material</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>327</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>384</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>365</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>327</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>379</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449322/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:09:20.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449322/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449322/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Ministry of Defence: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 24141, how many (a) unauthorised entries to military bases and (b) thefts or losses of classified material took place in (i) 2009, (ii) 2010, (iii) 2011, (iv) 2012 and (v) 2013.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449324","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>Fewer than five former employees of the Ministry of Defence applied to serve in foreign militaries between 1 April 2011 and 2 February 2016. Due to the low numbers, the breakdown by year has not been provided.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449324/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T13:19:51.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449324/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449324/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2016 to Question 23339, how many former employees of his Department applied to serve in foreign militaries under the Business Appointments process in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449325","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Type 23 capability sustainment programme will de-risk the introduction of the Type 26 Global Combat Ship, and deliver cost savings by bringing equipment into service in the Type 23 Frigates before transitioning to the Type 26. The Sea Ceptor Anti-Air Missile system and the Artisan 997 Air Surveillance Radar are examples of this.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449325/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:08:38.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449325/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449325/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has made an evaluation of which assets will be transferred from the fleet of T23 Frigates to the fleet of T26 Frigates.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","25217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449326","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-04","<p>Of the 82,000 tonnes of steel procured for the construction of the Queen Elizabeth Class Carriers, 77,000 tonnes was sourced from Tata Steel using their UK steel mills and processed in the UK by Dent Steel. The remaining 5,000 tonnes of specialised steel, not available from UK steel plants, was procured from Turkey (4,500 tonnes) and Spain (500 tonnes).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449326/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:15:10.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449326/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449326/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Aircraft Carriers: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the country of manufacture was of the non-British steel used in the construction of (a) HMS Queen Elizabeth and (b) HMS Prince of Wales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449327","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-04","<p>A number of measures to improve the reliability of the Type 45 Power and Propulsion systems have been identified. A programme was established in 2014 to implement these changes and continues to deliver positive results. In addition, and as announced in the Strategic Defence and Secuity Review 2015, we are planning to improve system resilience by adding upgraded diesel generators to provide further electrical generation capacity . Alternative technical options and a variety of delivery models are currently being explored with several competing industrial partners.</p><p>The total cost and timetable of implementing the diesel generator upgrade will be determined at the main investment decision. To reveal our current estimates would prejudice the commercial interests of the Department.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449327/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:18:42.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449327/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449327/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total cost was of alterations and refits to the six naval Type 45 destroyers to ensure they are fit for purpose.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","25063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449328","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 27 November 2014 to Question 215763.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449328/answer","20141127_215763_Armed_Forces_Uniforms[1].docx","20141127_215763_Armed_Forces_Uniforms[1].docx","20141127-QnA extract on Armed Forces Uniforms","20141127-QnA extract on Armed Forces Uniforms",,"2016-02-08T16:11:18.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449328/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449328/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Armed Forces: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the country of manufacture is of each type and item of military uniforms in each branch of the armed services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449329","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-04","<p>HMS Dauntless, HMS Duncan and HMS Defender all deployed to the Gulf in 2015 for 133, 270 and 69 days respectively. HMS Dauntless and HMS Duncan completed their deployments as planned and HMS Defender's deployment to the region, which began in October 2015, is continuing.</p><p>Throughout the year all Type 45 ships would have undertaken activities such as sea trials, training, engagement, provisioning or been in a maintenance period.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449329/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:23:14.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449329/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449329/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for how many days (a) HMS Daring, (b) HMS Dauntless, (c) HMS Diamond, (d) HMS Dragon, (e) HMS Defender and (f) HMS Duncan were deployed on operations in which theatre in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449330","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-04","<p>All complex systems suffer defects and require maintenance throughout their life, and warships are no exception. Operational Defects (OPDEFS) can vary in their categorisation and severity, covering minor ancillary components to major defects. The OPDEF process only applies to Ships in operational service, and I have therefore supplied the numbers for full years for Type 45 ships since their Commissioning.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7"><p>TOTAL OPDEFS ON TYPE 45 SHIPS IN THE LAST SIX YEARS</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Daring</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>186</p></td><td><p>184</p></td><td><p>278</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>156</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Dauntless</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>239</p></td><td><p>244</p></td><td><p>262</p></td><td><p>150</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Diamond</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>251</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Defender</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>209</p></td><td><p>224</p></td><td><p>202</p></td><td><p>209</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Dragon</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>268</p></td><td><p>235</p></td><td><p>124</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMS Duncan</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>NA</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>181</p></td><td><p>241</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We would not release more detailed information related to these figures as this would allow deductions to be made about a ship's capability and may affect operational security.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449330/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:11:45.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449330/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449330/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-01","Type 45 Destroyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many operational defects (a) HMS Daring, (b) HMS Dauntless, (c) HMS Diamond, (d) HMS Dragon, (e) HMS Defender and (f) HMS Duncan have reported in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25004"
