"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449485","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-04","<p>Statistics for assaults on prisoner on prisoner are published on an annual basis by calendar year in the Safety in Custody statistics bulletin annual assaults tables (see table 3.15 at the link below). <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/495430/safety-in-custody-assaults-dec-2014.xls</a>.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449485/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:39:36.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449485/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449485/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Swansea Prison: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) assaults and (b) serious assaults by prisoners on other prisoners were recorded at HMP Swansea during each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449486","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-04","<p>Information on the number and proportion of Black, Asian and minority Ethnic prison staff as at (i) 31 December 2010 and (ii) 30 September 2015 (latest available data) is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table: Number and proportion of BAME staff per band:</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Headcount of BAME Staff</strong></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><strong>BAME prison staff as a percentage of staff declaring their ethnicity</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Grade Type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>NOMS Band</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>31 December 2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>30 September 2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>31 December 2010</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>30 September 2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Operational</p></td><td><p>Band 2</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p>350</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>7.2</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 3</p></td><td><p>1030</p></td><td><p>760</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>5.5</p></td><td><p>5.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 4</p></td><td><p>160</p></td><td><p>120</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>4.6</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 5</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6</p></td><td><p>4.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 6</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 7</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>5.7</p></td><td><p>6.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 8</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.2</p></td><td><p>5.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 9</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>9.8</p></td><td><p>12.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 10</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 11</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>1810</p></td><td><p>1340</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>5.8</p></td><td><p>6.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non Operational</p></td><td><p>Band 2</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.4</p></td><td><p>9.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 3</p></td><td><p>350</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.1</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 4</p></td><td><p>170</p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.7</p></td><td><p>5.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 5</p></td><td><p>110</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>32.8</p></td><td><p>15.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 6</p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>8.7</p></td><td><p>5.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 7</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.1</p></td><td><p>17.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 8</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>7.7</p></td><td><p>8.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 9</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 10</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>41.2</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Band 11</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>830</p></td><td><p>510</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>7.4</p></td><td><p>7.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2640</p></td><td><p>1860</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6.2</p></td><td><p>6.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>All figures are rounded to the nearest 10, with numbers ending in 5 rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias. As with all HR databases, extracts are taken at a fixed point in time, to ensure consistency of reporting. However the database itself is dynamic, and where updates to the database are made late, subsequent to the taking of the extract, these updates will not be reflected in figures produced by the extract. For this reason, HR data are unlikely to be precisely accurate, and to present unrounded figures would be to overstate the accuracy of the figures. Rounding to 10 accurately depicts the level of certainty that is held with these figures.</p><p> </p><p>Totals are formed from unrounded parts prior to rounding. For this reason, rounded totals may not equal the sum of their rounded parts.</p><p> </p><p>~ denotes suppressed values. Values were suppressed if (i) the values were five or fewer or (ii) ethnicity declaration rates were below 60%. Low numbers are suppressed, in conjunction with the rounding policy to prevent disclosure in accordance with the Data Protection Act, 1998.</p><p> </p><p>Staff without a NOMS band include NPS graded staff and Senior Civil Servants.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449486/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:18:29.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449486/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449486/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Prison Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of prison staff at each band were BAME in (i) 2010 and (ii) the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449487","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Once the information requested is available I will write to the hon. Member for Romford and place a copy of that reply in the Library.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449487/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T14:37:31.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449487/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449487/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2016 to Question 22908, on prisoner escapes, if he will place a copy of the letter to the hon. Member for Romford in the Library.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","25231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449488","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-08","<p>The number of National Tactical Response Team (NTRG) members who have been injured during a callout over the last 2 years is set out in the table below</p><p> </p><p>No central records are held in respect of any injuries to Tornado staff, and this information cannot be obtained without disproportionate cost.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Members of NTRG who have been injured during a callout</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449488/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:13:57.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449488/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449488/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Prisons: Civil Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether any members of the (a) National Tactical Response Group and (b) Tornado Teams have been injured during a call out in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449489","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-04","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate costs.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449489/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:46:47.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449489/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449489/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Cardiff Prison: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners from HMP Cardiff attended A&E departments as a consequence of the use of psychoactive substances in each year from 2013 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449490","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The LAA does not routinely collect information on whether applicants for legal aid are victims of people charged with domestic violence.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2013, when people applied for legal aid they were not asked to declare whether domestic violence had occurred. Since 2013, applications for legal aid do not routinely request this information. Therefore the data requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>People seeking protective injunctions, like non-molestation orders, remain eligible for legal aid. Legal aid also remains available in private family cases that involve domestic violence. We have listened closely to any concerns about how the system has been operating, and made changes in response, such as making it easier to prove abuse and so get legal aid.</p><p> </p><p>The number of applications which require Domestic Violence evidence received and granted following LASPO, and figures for civil representation in the ‘Domestic Violence’ category both pre and post LASPO, are published in the official statistics on legal aid published quarterly on the Gov.uk website at the following link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/legal-aid-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/legal-aid-statistics</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449490/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T17:56:25.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449490/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449490/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Legal Aid Scheme: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for legal aid were (a) made by and (b) granted to victims of people charged with domestic violence in each local authority area in the North West Police Authority in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449491","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government is committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 and will do so as soon as possible.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449491/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:12:02.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449491/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449491/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department plans to commence section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","25179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449492","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-08","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p><br></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449492/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:14:18.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449492/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449492/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Prisoners: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners in England and Wales were admitted to accident and emergency departments as a consequence of the use of psychoactive substances in (a) 2012, (b) 2013, (c) 2014 and (d) 2015.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","25162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449493","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>I wrote to Police and Crime Commissioners on 22 January 2016 to confirm their victims’ services commissioning grants for 2016-17. We have protected the total budget for victims’ services. PCCs allocations have been held at the 2015-16 level of £63.15m. PCCs will also be allocated an additional £4.7m to support victims of child sexual abuse.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449493/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T14:52:26.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449493/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449493/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Police and Crime Commissioners: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he will announce the level of grant funding available to Police and Crime Commissioners; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","25197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449494","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>As noted in the Chancellor’s Autumn Statement, the figure of £2 billion a year is an insurance industry estimate of the cost of dealing with road traffic related personal injury claims.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be publishing an impact assessment alongside its consultation on the whiplash reforms announced in the Autumn Statement in due course.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449494/answer",,,,,"25196","2016-02-09T14:25:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449494/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449494/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to his Department's press release of 28 December 2015, Insurers vow to pass on whiplash reform saving, what the evidential basis is for the Government's statement that whiplash claims cost the country £2 billion a year.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","25195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449495","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>As noted in the Chancellor’s Autumn Statement, the figure of £2 billion a year is an insurance industry estimate of the cost of dealing with road traffic related personal injury claims.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be publishing an impact assessment alongside its consultation on the whiplash reforms announced in the Autumn Statement in due course.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449495/answer",,,,,"25195","2016-02-09T14:25:05.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449495/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449495/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on what proportion of the £2 billion cost of whiplash claims comes from (a) genuine claims and (b) fraudulent claims.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","25196"
