"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449502","Prime Minister","false","2016-02-08","<p>Details of my meetings with external organisations are released on a quarterly basis and can be accessed via the gov.uk website.</p><p>My officials and special advisers have meetings with a wide range of organisations and individuals on a range of subjects.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449502/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:46:04.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449502/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449502/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-02-01","Soft Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what discussions (a) he, (b) Edward Llewellyn, (c) Camilla Cavendish and (d) staff of the Number 10 Policy Unit have had with representatives of (i) the Food and Drink Federation, (ii) Coca-Cola, (iii) PepsiCo and (iv) the British Soft Drinks Association in each of the last 18 months; and what the subject was of each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","24984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449503","Scotland Office","false","2016-02-05","<p>I have regular discussions with the Scottish Government’s Deputy First Minister on all aspects of our implementation of the Smith Commission Agreement, including the devolution of responsibility for abortion law to the Scottish Parliament. UK and Scottish Government officials will continue to work closely on this issue.</p><p> </p><p>I have had discussions with representatives of women’s organisations on this matter. However, with the transfer of responsibility to the Scottish Parliament, it is primarily for the Scottish Government to take forward engagement with interested parties. Scottish Government Ministers have met with representatives of a number of stakeholder organisations to discuss the devolution of abortion law and the delivery of abortion services in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449503/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T12:40:09.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449503/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449503/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-02-01","Abortion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with (a) ministers in the Scottish Government and (b) women's organisations on devolving competence for abortion legislation to Scotland.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","24983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449504","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>In <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/April_2014" target="_blank">April 2014</a> English local highway authorities were invited to bid for a share of a £168 million Pothole Fund for 2014/15 to repair local roads in England as announced in the March 2014 Budget.</p><p> </p><p>An announcement was made in June 2014. All local highway authorities received a share of the funding as set out in the table available at the following weblink:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/321677/pothole-funding-2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/321677/pothole-funding-2014.pdf</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449504/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T10:40:48.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449504/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449504/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many and what proportion of local authorities that bid for pothole funding in 2014-15 were successful.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","24985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449505","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>On the 10 November the Secretary of State announced an Emissions Testing Programme to look for “defeat devices” and improve our understanding of the real world emissions performance of vehicles used in the UK. This investigation is vital in restoring public confidence. To ensure the independence of the testing, the Department is funding the programme and neither the cars nor the testing facilities will be provided by the vehicle industry themselves.</p><p> </p><p>Ongoing testing of VW Group vehicles outside the Department for Transport Emissions Testing Programme and for which the Vehicle Certification Agency is the approval authority (Skoda), will be funded by the manufacturer on a case by case basis.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449505/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:53:44.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449505/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449505/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions the Vehicle and Certification Agency has had with Volkswagen on the funding of the vehicle retesting programme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","25018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449506","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>Funding for the British Transport Police is not derived directly from a specific Government grant but from holders of police service agreements. However, during the recent spending review, the Department has made clear to the British Transport Police Authority that it considers that appropriate efficiencies should be identified and made. However, it has also emphasised that any efficiencies should not materially impact on the operational policing capability of the British Transport Police, including in relation to counter-terrorist activity.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449506/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:56:49.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449506/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449506/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","British Transport Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 2 of the actions of the meeting of the Rail Delivery Group National Taskforce of 30 September 2015, what the effect of the Autumn Statement and Spending Review 2015 is on the funding of the British Transport Police.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","25019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449507","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>Details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published on a quarterly basis and are available via the gov.uk website.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since July 2015, representatives of Uber have had one meeting with Department for Transport officials.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449507/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:32:59.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449507/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449507/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many meetings Ministers and officials of his Department have had with representatives of Uber since July 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","24989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449508","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Department for Transport is providing over £6.1 billion funding to local highway authorities in England between 2015 and 2021 for local highways maintenance. This includes repairing roads that might be damaged due to severe winter weather. This funding includes £50 million per annum from 2016 to 2021 for a dedicated Pothole Action Fund as announced in the recent Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is currently working up criteria on how the Pothole Action Fund will operate and an announcement will be made in due course on this. Therefore no applications have yet been submitted nor have any decisions been made on how this funding will be allocated.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449508/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T14:42:25.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449508/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449508/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many local authorities have applied for funding from the permanent pothole fund since the announcement of that fund in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015; and how many applications for such funding his Department expects to be approved in (a) 2015-16 and (b) the 2015-20 Parliament.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","25048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449509","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>Further to the answer to Question 24477 the attached tables list railway stations by region that are fitted with ITSO-compliant smartcard readers.</p><p> </p><p>The table contains 710 rail stations – this is 8 fewer than the previous answer, because in the answer provided to the Hon. member on 2nd February, three stations operated by more than one train operator were split into multiple entries and the five stations in addition to Gatwick Airport that were involved in January’s extension of Oyster were also listed twice. This duplication has been removed.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449509/answer","025069 - Tables of Rail Stations in England fitted with ITSO.docx","025069 - Tables of Rail Stations in England fitted with ITSO.docx","List of Railways Stations in Eng fitted with ITSO","List of Railways Stations in Eng fitted with ITSO",,"2016-02-04T17:07:08.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449509/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449509/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24477, which railway stations in which regions are fitted with ITSO-compliant smartcard readers.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","25069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449510","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Rail Regulation Call for Evidence which was published on GOV.UK on 10 December 2015 stated that the project would be ‘run in parallel with the Shaw Report and conclude by March 2016’.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449510/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:11:29.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449510/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449510/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Office of Rail and Road","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects his Department's review of the Office of Rail and Road to conclude.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","25070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449511","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-11","<p>The British Road Safety Statement was published on 21 December 2015. It includes a number of actions to be delivered across government and in partnership with others in private, public and civil society organisations.</p><p>We are currently setting up monitoring arrangements.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449511/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T15:43:57.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449511/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449511/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how his Department will monitor implementation of the measures set out in the Government's British Road Safety Statement, published in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449512","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>I intend to convene a round table in March, the details of which are currently being finalised. The round table will discuss the topic, and help to inform the Department’s thinking and the work it plans to do later this year to examine more closely the legal and financial implications of alternative approaches.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449512/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:01:56.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449512/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449512/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress the Government has made on an impact analysis and consultation on changes to current pavement parking legislation since the withdrawal of the Pavement Parking (Protection of Vulnerable Pedestrians) Bill.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","25000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449513","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Depending on the franchise, we measure the level of services provided by the performance against the set benchmarks (capacity, cancellations and delay minutes), and/or the Public Performance Measure. Some franchises are also measured against the National Passenger Survey results.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449513/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:22:23.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449513/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449513/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the criteria are by which his Department measures the level of service provided by rail franchises operating.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","25182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449514","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government Buying Standards (GBS) are recommended for the wider public sector but outside central government they<br>are not obligatory.</p><p> </p><p>The current GBS has been in place since 2012. As stated in the recent publication “Improving air quality in the UK”, revised standards for cars and vans will be published this year. Revisions will encourage cleaner and safer vehicles where appropriate.</p><p /><p />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449514/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T10:57:35.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449514/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449514/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","NHS: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether recent changes to Government Buying Standards to encourage the uptake of safer vehicles will apply to the NHS.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449515","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Section 55 of the Railways Act 1993 (as amended) gives the Secretary of State power to make an Enforcement Order where a train operator contravenes a term of the franchise agreement. Such an Order may require the train operator to take specified steps to address the contravention and can include a requirement to pay a penalty if the Train Operator contravenes the Order.</p><p> </p><p>Section 57A of the Railways Act 1993 (as amended) gives the Secretary of State a separate power to impose a penalty for contravention of a term of the franchise agreement as an alternative to making an Enforcement Order or in addition to such an Order (provided that the Order does not include a penalty provision).</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 no train operator has been required to make a payment for breach of an Enforcement Order under section 55. Some 13 Enforcement Orders under Section 55 have been issued, and one train operator has been required to make a penalty payment imposed under section 57A.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449515/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:26:36.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449515/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449515/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what statutory arrangements are in place to penalise rail franchises which consistently perform poorly; and how often such arrangements have been called on since 2010.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","25181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449516","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-11","<p>The main regulatory aspects of driving for work are enforced by the Police. They take the lead in the investigating road traffic incidents and can refer cases to the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) if they believe there are clear employer management failings contributing to the incident.</p><p> </p><p>In our British Road Safety Statement, published in December, we highlighted helping employers to reduce road related collisions at work as a priority. We will start this process by evaluating existing safer driving for work schemes to understand what works, with a view to promoting existing good practice to employer networks and other occupational drivers.</p><p> </p><p>The government has no plans to extend the scope of the Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations [RIDDOR] to cover work related road incidents.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449516/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T15:32:42.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449516/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449516/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Roads: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what action he intends to take against employers who neglect their responsibilities for occupational road safety; and whether he plans to support an extension of the Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations 2013 to include work-related road casualties.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449517","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-08","<p>The government has a manifesto commitment to reduce the number of cyclists and other road users killed or injured on our roads every year and we published our British Road Safety Statement, setting out our priorities in achieving that goal on 21 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Statement describes a series of actions to be undertaken across government over the short, medium and long term. Several of these contribute specifically to cyclist safety, including:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Continue with £50 million investment to deliver Bikeability training in schools, providing the next generation of cyclists with the skills and confidence to cycle safely on local roads</li><li>Consult on dangerous in-car mobile phone use with a view to increasing penalties for offenders</li><li>Consult on legislative changes on HGV sideguards</li><li>Encourage development and implementation of improved HGV design</li><li>Develop and test new Hazard Perception Test materials to improve learner drivers’ awareness of developing hazards in varying weather and lighting conditions, and broaden the scope of scenarios providing experience of real life situations such as encountering vulnerable road users</li><li>Our commitment to produce a Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy setting out our objectives, activities and funding available for cycling and walking in England in the long term. The Strategy will be published in the summer and will include details of how the £300m committed in the recent Spending Review will be invested to support cycling and walking.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449517/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:21:59.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449517/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449517/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Cycling: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which particular measures his Department has included in its Road Safety Statement of 21 December 2015 to help reduce the number of cyclists killed and injured every year.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449518","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>Rail passengers are protected by the National Rail Conditions of Carriage and also the terms of the Ticketing and Settlement Agreement (TSA), an inter-operator agreement that governs, among other things, the retail of rail tickets. These provisions safeguard passengers’ interests by requiring train operators to provide clear information and to sell the most suitable ticket for their journey. This will, in many cases, be the cheapest ticket. Operators are required, under the terms of the TSA, to ask sufficient suitable questions in order to ascertain and sell the best ticket for each passenger’s needs.</p><p>In a response to my challenge in December 2014, the rail industry worked with the Office of Rail and Road (ORR) to develop a Code of Practice on Retail Information, published in March 2015. The ORR wrote to all train operators in May 2015 to establish levels of compliance with the Code and published an update on progress in September 2015.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449518/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:16:42.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449518/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449518/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure train companies have simple and easily comprehensible ticketing policies and offer the cheapest ticket for any requested journey.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","25142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449519","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Coventry South (Jim Cunningham) on 29 January 2016 UIN 24320, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=24320" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=24320</a>.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449519/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T12:57:40.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449519/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449519/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to make it easier for passengers to access the cheapest tickets available for any requested journey.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","25141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449520","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Department does not hold the information requested. However, we will continue to push operators to ensure passengers are aware of compensation arrangements and claim where entitled to do so under the Delay/Repay scheme as set out on the Southern’s website: <a href="https://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/customer-services/delay-repay/delay-repay-form" target="_blank">https://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/customer-services/delay-repay/delay-repay-form</a>.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449520/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:50:11.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449520/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449520/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many passengers submitted Delay/Repay claims to Southern Railway in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14 and (e) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","25128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449521","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>On 20 January 2016 the Mayor of London announced his plans for modernising and enhancing London’s private hire vehicle industry. In these plans the Mayor recognised the need to investigate ways to address the congestion and air quality impacts of the increasing number of private hire vehicles in London without capping numbers. The Government will discuss with the Mayor any options that are proposed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government supports competition and growth in the taxi and private hire sector although we are aware of a range of factors that could affect the private hire market in London, including raising standards and removing exemptions from the Congestion Charge. The Department’s Best Practice Guidance for taxi and private hire vehicle licensing advises licensing authorities that licensing requirements which are unduly stringent will tend unreasonably to restrict the supply of taxi and private hire vehicle services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449521/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T11:01:24.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449521/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449521/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2016 to Question 23012, which options the Government is discussing with the Mayor; and what information his Department holds on the potential effect of other ways of influencing the private hire vehicle market that do not require new legislation.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","25098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449522","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-04","<p>I wrote to the Rail Delivery Group on 2nd February 2016, seeking views on how the rail industry intends to meet the Government’s expectations on ticketing, which I outlined in a speech on 26th January. My letter to the Rail Delivery Group is attached, and a web link to my speech, is set out below. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-death-of-the-tangerine-ticket?dm_t=0,0,0,0,0" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/the-death-of-the-tangerine-ticket?dm_t=0,0,0,0,0</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449522/answer","025119 - 160202 CP to David Brown RDG.pdf","025119 - 160202 CP to David Brown RDG.pdf","Letter from Rail Minister to Rail Delivery Group","Letter from Rail Minister to Rail Delivery Group",,"2016-02-04T17:16:31.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449522/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449522/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the minutes of the meeting of the Rail Delivery Group of 22 December 2015, whether the letter outlining the Government's expectations on ticketing referred to in that document has been sent.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","25119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449523","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department for Transport, as a founding member of Euro NCAP, continues to take a keen interest in the organisation through membership of the Board of Directors.</p><p> </p><p>Euro NCAP has regularly updated the assessment criteria to reflect new technologies and improved designs. As such it has been fundamental to improving road safety of new cars in the UK and the organisation provides a valuable source of information to UK consumers which the government fully supports.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449523/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T10:46:42.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449523/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449523/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-01","European New Car Assessment Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, in what way his Department participates in the European New Car Assessment Programme; and what his policy is on changes to the criteria for awarding five stars for safety.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","25242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449524","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government has incurred approximately £50,626 in legal costs in the Court of Appeal proceedings in the case of <em>Rutherford and others v Secretary of State for Work and Pensions and A v Secretary of State for Work and Pensions</em> [2016] EWCA CIV 29.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that this figure includes VAT where this is payable (e.g. on Counsel’s fees) but does not include costs attributable to the time spent by Government advisory lawyers on this case, as time spent by such advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributed to individual cases.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449524/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:59:42.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449524/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449524/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Department for Work and Pensions: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's legal costs were in the case Susan Rutherford, Paul Rutherford and Warren Todd and Appellant A v Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","25249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449525","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The policy is still under development and full impact and equality assessments will be undertaken in due course.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449525/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T11:53:49.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449525/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449525/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Supported Housing: Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answers of 28 January 2016 to Questions 24029 and 24048, what (a) financial assessment, (b) cost-benefit assessment and (c) impact assessment his Department has carried out on the proposal to cap the cost of local housing allowance for people living in sheltered and supported housing.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","25127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449526","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>This information is not available.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449526/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:58:48.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449526/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449526/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of the cost resulting from the reduction in the work allowance of universal credit relates to (a) new claimants to universal credit, (b) current recipients of universal credit and (c) current tax credit recipients naturally migrated onto universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","25154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449527","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-08","<p>The information is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449527/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:47:23.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449527/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449527/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Means-tested Benefits: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the administrative costs of delivering means-tested benefits were in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","25133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449528","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>Natural migration occurs where people have had a significant change of circumstances that would previously have triggered a new claim to benefits or tax credits. They would always have had their entitlement recalculated based on a new set of rules. That principle is maintained in Universal Credit, and therefore transitional protection is not appropriate. Universal Credit is already proving better than the system it replaces with claimants moving into work faster and earning more. It also provides a seamless taper as well as better support for childcare.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449528/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:57:12.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449528/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449528/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit: Transitional Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Government plans to provide transitional protection for tax credit recipients who have been naturally migrated onto universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","25155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449529","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>Claimants who go online can find a summary of the Carer’s Allowance earnings rules on GOV.UK - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/carers-allowance/eligibility" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/carers-allowance/eligibility</a>. Those people who want to make their claim in writing are sent similar information on earnings with their claim pack. In addition, the letter claimants get when they are awarded Carer’s Allowance informs them of the need to report employment to the department and they are reminded of the need to report earnings and the relevant limits in the annual “uprating” letter.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449529/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T13:16:41.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449529/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449529/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Carer's Allowance: Earnings Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the oral contribution of 7 December 2015, Official Report, column 699, if he will place in the Library summary information on (a) earnings limits for recipients of carer's allowance and (b) the means by which claimants of that allowance are advised of those limits.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","25143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449530","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The events that can trigger a change of circumstances depend on many factors. They are similar to the circumstances that would trigger a new claim to existing benefits or tax credits, which would also lead to a recalculation of entitlement.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449530/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:06:50.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449530/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449530/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, under what change of circumstances a tax credit claimant will naturally be migrated onto universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","25156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449531","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The information could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449531/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:06:42.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449531/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449531/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of times a universal credit claimant has been paid housing benefit and housing costs at the same time resulting in an overpayment of housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","25157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449532","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong>The Veterans Interview Programme was launched in November 2012 as a non-political, cross party initiative. It was purposefully set up with light governance arrangements to ensure the focus is on support for veterans and not on completing paperwork. Although DWP provides support for the scheme on this basis, employers are not required to let the Department know once they have decided to take part in the programme. As a result we do not have the information available to answer this question.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449532/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T14:47:08.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449532/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449532/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Employment Schemes: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many companies have signed up to the Veterans Guaranteed Interview scheme in each year since its inception.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","25198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449533","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department does not prescribe how providers delivering welfare to work provision train their staff.</p><p><em> </em></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449533/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:57:03.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449533/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449533/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Ingeus: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what training is provided to new Ingeus advisers in advising clients with mental health issues; and what plans are in place to ensure all Ingeus advisers are given such training.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","25212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449534","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The number of people on benefits is driven by a range of factors. Because of this, the programme measures progress by the successful achievement of milestones of its delivery plan rather than targets for numbers of claimants.</p><p /> <p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449534/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:02:13.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449534/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449534/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants his Department estimates will have moved on to universal credit by the end of 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449535","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government is committed to working to eliminate child poverty and improve life chances for children. Work remains the best route out of poverty, and Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work. Evidence shows claimants move into work significantly faster and earn more than under the current system. In addition, from April 2016 Universal Credit provides for 85% of childcare costs meaning more support for hardworking families.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449535/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:02:50.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449535/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449535/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, following changes to universal credit taking effect in April 2016, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the number of children in poverty of the introduction of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449536","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>All benefit new claims lines have 0800 numbers and are therefore free whether claimants call from mobile phones or landlines, with the exception of Universal Credit which has an 0345 number as the expectation is that claims are made online.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449536/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:12:27.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449536/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449536/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Social Security Benefits: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 28 January 2016 to Question 23991, whether calls to make a claim for benefit are free for all (a) pay-as-you-go mobile telephones, (b) monthly contract mobile telephones and (c) landline telephones.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449537","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>The published statistics in relation to Employment and Support Allowance reconsideration clearance times in the Great Britain are in the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-reconsiderations-of-dwp-benefit-decisions-data-to-october-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-reconsiderations-of-dwp-benefit-decisions-data-to-october-2014</a></p><p> </p><p>The information requested in relation to other benefit reconsiderations is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The latest information from Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service for appeal clearance times for the areas that cover Ogmore, Wales and the UK in the period April – September 2015, is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Area<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>Waiting Time (Weeks)</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cardiff</p></td><td><p>16.6</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Port Talbot</p></td><td><p>18.5</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>17.7</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><em>Source: HMCTS MI System Feb 16</em> Note: The data is normally registered to the venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service cannot retrieve data based on the appellant’s actual address, but can produce reports detailing the numbers of cases that were dealt with at one of its Regional centres. The majority of appellants living in the Ogmore area have their appeals heard in the Cardiff venues, though some may be heard in Port Talbot.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449537/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T15:17:32.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449537/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449537/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Social Security Benefits: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average length of time to wait is for a reconsideration of a benefit decision by (a) his Department and (b) a tribunal hearing in (i) Ogmore and (ii) Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","25037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449538","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The First-tier Tribunal – Social Security and Child Support (SSCS) administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service, hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ decisions on a range of benefits including Personal Independence Payment (PIP).</p><p> </p><p>The majority of appellants living in the Ogmore area have their SSCS appeals heard in the Cardiff venues though some may be heard in Port Talbot.</p><p> </p><p>The following table provides information on the proportion of PIP appeals which were decided in favour of the appellant in Cardiff and Port Talbot venues and in Wales between July and September 2015 (the latest period for which figures are available).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Percentage of PIP appeals found in favour of the appellant</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cardiff</p></td><td><p>Port Talbot</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July – September 2015</p></td><td><p>75%</p></td><td><p>75%</p></td><td><p>73%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note: SSCS data are recorded by the office that dealt with the case, and if the case went to oral hearing, the location of the Tribunal hearing is normally the hearing venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. Data cannot be retrieved based on the appellant’s actual address but can be produced detailing the numbers of cases that were dealt with at one of our Regional centres or heard at a specific venue.</p><p> </p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data available.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449538/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T17:52:17.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449538/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449538/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-01","Personal Independence Payment: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of personal independence payment appeals were successful in (a) Ogmore and (b) Wales in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","25036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449539","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-03","<p>In 2015-16 no households will be exempt from the benefit cap due to a claimant being in receipt of Carer’s Allowance. The exemption from the benefit cap for those in receipt of Carer’s Allowance will be introduced later this year, subject to Parliamentary approval.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449539/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T11:48:42.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449539/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449539/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Social Security Benefits: Carer's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households will be exempted from the household benefit cap in 2015-16 due to the claimant being in receipt of carer's allowance (a) in total and (b) in each English local authority.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","24974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449540","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government is committed to the implementation of the PPF long service cap. Before the primary legislation can be brought into force, a number of changes need to be made to secondary legislation, so that it will operate as expected in all cases. Therefore we cannot, at this time, commit to a particular implementation date.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449540/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:06:10.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449540/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449540/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-01","Pension Protection Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will implement the provisions of the Pensions Act 2014 on removal of the cap to the Pension Protection Fund.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","24981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449940","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-04","<p>The government is investing nearly £200 million to help communities recover from Storm Desmond and Storm Eva. The Barnett Formula has been applied to this funding in the normal way.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449940/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T15:43:20.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449940/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449940/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-01","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Barnett Formula applies to government funding of emergency flood relief.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","903456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449941","Church Commissioners","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Church of England’s Cathedral and Church Buildings Division developed the open and sustainable churches initiative five years ago, and now 80% of churches provide a function beyond purely worship, with 54% of Anglican parishes running at least one organised activity to address social or community need. Churches are being used as citizen’s advice bureau, post offices, shops, night shelters and food banks. Two recent examples of local projects where the Church has opening its buildings for the wider community in the Lincoln Diocese include:</p><p>St Peter &amp; Paul Church, Algarkirk has been successful in getting through the first stage of HLF funding for a project to host a local heritage center, explaining the history of the area including an oral history project and fascinating details about this Grade I medieval church. The Parish Church has a collection of Victorian stained glass of national quality and furnishings by J.G. Grace who also furnished the Houses of Parliament.</p><p>All Saints Church, Winterton is a Grade 1 Medieval church which has been restored with new community facilities installed to make it more accessible with the help of HLF and other grants.</p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449941/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T13:51:38.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449941/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449941/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-02-01","Church of England: Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what steps the Church of England is taking to ensure that its buildings are open for wider community use.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","903466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449958","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>In November 2015 Defra published an implementation plan highlighting progress in the first year of the National Pollinator Strategy. As an example, over half of mid–tier applications to our new £900 million Countryside Stewardship scheme, launched in July 2015, contain the Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package. Monitoring and evaluation of the scheme will include measures to establish the impact on pollinators.</p><p> </p><p>The Strategy has also taken steps to promote public awareness and engagement, including holding the first Pollinator Awareness Week in July 2015.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449958/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T17:49:35.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449958/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/449958/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Pollinators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the National Pollinator Strategy since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","903446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450279","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Electoral Commission recently wrote to the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Committee, following that Committee’s recent evidence session, on a number of issues, including the potential impact of the date of the referendum if it were to be held in June. A copy of the letter is available on the Committee’s website.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450279/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T12:14:13.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450279/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450279/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2016-02-01","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what recent assessment the Electoral Commission has made of the potential effect of the date of the EU referendum on mayoral, local, and devolved institutions' elections.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","903473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450581","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>UK-led Common Fisheries Policy reforms have given UK fishermen a more sustainable long-term future.</p><p> </p><p>The inshore fleet will particularly benefit from an extra 1,000 tonnes of quota this year. This comes on top of the permanent transfer of under-used quota to the Under-10s, which was worth an extra 678 tonnes in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, over £100m of European (EMFF) Funding is now available to support the UK catching, processing and aquaculture sectors.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450581/answer",,,,,"903459","2016-02-04T14:18:50.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450581/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450581/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Fisheries: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support UK fishermen (a) in general and (b) in the under 10 metre fleet.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sheryll Murray","South East Cornwall","Mrs Sheryll Murray","903461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450582","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>As a result of the Government’s £2.3 billion, six year capital investment programme more than 420,000 acres of farmland will be better protected by 2021.</p><p>Together with our investment in the last parliament this means that more than a million acres of farmland will be better protected from flooding over this decade.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450582/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T11:48:34.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450582/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450582/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Flood Control: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many acres of farmland she plans will be protected by government investment in flood defences over the next six years.","false","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","Newark","Robert Jenrick","903463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450583","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government remains committed to tackling wildlife crime.</p><p>We are currently allocating our Spending Review settlement. Future funding for the National Wildlife Crime Unit will be decided as part of that process.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450583/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T14:10:26.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450583/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450583/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","National Wildlife Crime Unit: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to continue funding the National Wildlife Crime Unit.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","903457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450584","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>We continue to support our hard-working dairy farmers by reducing inspections, extending the system of tax averaging, and opening new export markets.</p><p> </p><p>The £26.2 million aid package we secured from the European Commission has helped to provide some immediate relief. A number of supermarkets have also pledged to pay a premium over and above the current market price.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450584/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T14:25:45.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450584/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450584/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress she has made on ensuring that farmers receive a fair price for milk.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","903458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450585","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>UK-led Common Fisheries Policy reforms have given UK fishermen a more sustainable long-term future.</p><p> </p><p>The inshore fleet will particularly benefit from an extra 1,000 tonnes of quota this year. This comes on top of the permanent transfer of under-used quota to the Under-10s, which was worth an extra 678 tonnes in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, over £100m of European (EMFF) Funding is now available to support the UK catching, processing and aquaculture sectors.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450585/answer",,,,,"903461","2016-02-04T14:18:50.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450585/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450585/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Fisheries: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support UK fishermen (a) in general and (b) in the under 10 metre fleet.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","903459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450586","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-04","<p>May I pay tribute to the community of Earby and their fortitude following the terrible floods this Christmas.</p><p> </p><p>We have been working closely with the local community and partners in Earby to investigate options for reducing the risk from all sources of flooding.</p><p> </p><p>We have allocated £50,000 to this study.</p><p> </p><p>The study will also update the flood map for Earby, improve flood warning and improve planning decisions.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, the Environment Agency is carrying out £500k of work to repair and reduce the risk of blockage of the Victoria Clough culvert.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450586/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:49:56.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450586/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450586/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-01","Flood Control: Earby","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of flood defences in Earby.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","903460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448921","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-02","<p>Quick Reaction Alert (QRA) Typhoon aircraft from RAF Lossiemouth and RAF Coningsby launched to intercept aircraft on 12 days in 2015.</p><p>I am withholding further details as deterrence is a principal function of QRA and QRA is in turn an integral part of the air defence of the UK. The disclosure of information that might compromise the QRA deterrent capability would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448921/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-02T15:40:31.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448921/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448921/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on how many occasions in the last 12 months and from which airfields aircraft of the Quick Reaction Alert have been scrambled, and for what purpose on every occasion.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL5632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448922","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>We do not collate information centrally about the numbers and locations of women’s centres across the UK or the services that they offer.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that future funding for women’s centres should lie at the local level, as local experts know what works in their community and how best to deliver services. We are encouraging and supporting areas to bring together local agencies in the criminal justice, statutory and third sectors to develop a joined-up, multi-agency approach to address the often complex needs of female offenders.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448922/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T15:51:15.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448922/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448922/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-29","Women's Centres","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Corston review in 2007, how many women's centres there are in the UK; where those centres are located; to what extent those centres support women on remand or serving community sentences; and what plans they have to establish additional centres.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448923","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference met on one occasion during 2007, 26 February in Dundalk. This was the last time that the body met.</p><p> </p><p>Details of Ministerial attendees and the topics discussed were published in a Joint Communiqué between the two Governments. A copy of this has been placed in the Library (along with copies of all other Joint Communiques published since 1998).</p><p> </p><p>Although a range of issues were discussed, no formal actions were listed. The focus however at the time was the drive towards devolution and the Conference urged all political leaders to act with courage and determination in order to attain this. Assembly elections subsequently took place in May 2007.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448923/answer",,,,,"HL6044","2016-02-23T14:15:38.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448923/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448923/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-29","British Irish Intergovernmental Conference","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will place the minutes of the British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference since 1998 in the Library of the House.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL5634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448924","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>In the UK, The Equality Act 2010 legally protects people from discrimination in the workplace and in wider society.</p><p> </p><p>The Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) has many commitments that recall that all persons are equal before the law and are entitled without any discrimination to the equal protection of the law.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448924/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-23T18:00:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448924/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448924/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-29","Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether membership of the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe requires them to regard all citizens in the UK to be equal and thus requiring equal treatment by law.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL5635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448925","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>In this context there is no difference between people ‘in’ Northern Ireland and people ‘of’ Northern Ireland.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448925/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-23T18:00:17.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448925/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448925/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-29","Equality: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 27 November 2015 (HL3723), what difference, if any, there is between people in Northern Ireland and people of Northern Ireland in the application of their policies.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL5636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448926","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Civil Service has a significant presence across the UK and we are considering how new government hubs, in strategic locations across the country, will help to make sure that we have an efficient and effective Civil Service at the same time as we consolidate the government estate.</p><p>Any proposed relocation is done based on the operational needs of Departments.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448926/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-15T12:06:30.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448926/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448926/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-29","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative, what are their policies for the decentralisation of civil servants.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448927","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government has not published guidance for local authorities about charging for Freedom of Information requests.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448927/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-29T12:15:36.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448927/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448927/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-29","Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have guidelines for local authorities about charging for responses to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448928","Department for Education","false","2016-02-04","<p>All state schools, including academies and free schools, must provide a daily act of collective worship for all registered pupils up to the age of 18. Parents have the right to withdraw their children from all or any part of collective worship, and sixth-form pupils have the right to withdraw themselves from collective worship.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448928/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T13:40:51.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448928/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-29","Schools: Collective Worship","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 20 January (HL5274), whether it is still a legal requirement to have a daily act of collective worship in academies, free schools and maintained schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448929","Department for Education","false","2016-02-10","<p>The law provides a number of safeguards to ensure that all children receive a suitable full-time education. These are set out in Chapters I and II of Part VI of the Education Act 1996, and include:</p><ul><li><p>a duty on local authorities to make arrangements to establish, as far as it is possible to do so, the identities of children of compulsory school age in their area who are not receiving suitable education (Section 436A);</p></li><li><p>a duty on local authorities to arrange suitable education for all children of compulsory school age who may not for any period receive it, unless such arrangements are made for them (Section 19);</p></li><li><p>a duty on parents to ensure that their child of compulsory school age is receiving suitable full-time education, either at school or otherwise (Section 7);</p></li><li><p>provision for a local authority to issue a School Attendance Order to a parent where it is not satisfied that a child of compulsory age is receiving a suitable education (Section 437); and</p></li><li><p>provision for the prosecution of a parent who has failed to secure their child's regular attendance at school (Section 444).</p></li></ul><p>Statutory guidance requires local authorities to have robust procedures and policies in place to enable them to carry out their duty to identify children of compulsory school age in their area who are not receiving suitable education (<em>Children Missing Education, 2015)</em>.</p><p>Under the <em>Education (Pupil Registration) (England) Regulations 2006</em>, schools have a duty to inform their local authority, at agreed intervals, of the details of pupils who are regularly absent from school or have missed 10 school days or more without permission. Schools must also notify the authority if a pupil is to be deleted from the admission register in certain circumstances.</p><p>We are taking steps to ensure the system is as robust as it can be when it comes to protecting young people, while at the same time safeguarding the rights of parents to determine how and where to educate their children. The Department for Education is currently consulting on proposals to strengthen further the <em>Education (Pupil Registration) (England) Regulations 2006</em> in order to require schools to inform local authorities under all grounds when a child’s name is deleted from a school register.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448929/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-10T16:25:08.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448929/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448929/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-29","Children: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what safeguards are in place to prevent children either never going to school or going missing from school.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448930","Department for Education","false","2016-02-04","<p>When parents elect to educate children at home, they assume financial responsibility for their children’s education. Local authorities are not funded specifically to provide financial support to those parents who educate at home.</p><p>If a child has special needs, financial assistance may well be appropriate. If the child has a statement of special educational needs or an Education and Health Care (EHC) Plan which specifies home education, or one which specifies a school but the parents have chosen to educate their child at home, then financial support to the parents may help discharge the authority’s duty to ensure that the child’s needs are met.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448930/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T13:40:02.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448930/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-29","Home Education: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what financial support is available for children whose parents choose for their child to be tutored at home.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448931","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>HMRC does not enter into special arrangements with companies.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448931/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-12T14:32:14.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448931/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448931/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Companies: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many companies have made special arrangements with HMRC to pay tax owed, and how the arrangements are assessed as reasonable and fair to the taxpayer in general as well as to the company concerned.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448932","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government is determined to crack down on the compensation culture and insurance fraud.. We therefore announced, in the Autumn Statement, that we will limit the right to damages for pain, suffering and loss of amenity in low value whiplash claims and raise the small claims limit for personal injury claims to £5,000.</p><p> </p><p>These reforms build on previous measures taken forward by the Ministry of Justice to control costs, strengthen the medical evidence process and reduce incentives to pursue fraudulent and unnecessary whiplash claims.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consult on the detail of the new measures in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448932/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-11T14:58:48.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448932/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448932/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-29","Personal Injury: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are planning to take to end fraudulent whiplash insurance claims.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448933","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-03","<p>The government is committed to creating a share owning democracy in Britain. The Lloyds Banking Group share offer will help build that by giving the general public the chance to have a greater stake in our economy and encouraging long-term share ownership.</p><p> </p><p>However, given ongoing events in financial markets, now is not the right time to sell shares to retail investors. We have always been clear that sales are dependent on market conditions and the timing of the offer will be kept under review in light of this.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448933/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T16:42:17.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448933/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448933/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Lloyds Banking Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the expected timetable for the Lloyds Banking Group share offer.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL5644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448934","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>Decisions about these separate matters will be taken on their individual merits. Further information on the Government’s proposals for a sale of the Green Investment Bank (GIB) is provided in our November 2015 policy statement on the future of GIB and in the Government’s response to the Environmental Audit Committee’s report on the future of GIB. Both documents can be found on the GIB pages of the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448934/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:30:04.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448934/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448934/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the market conditions affecting the Government's decision to postpone the privatisation of Lloyds Bank on the proposed privatisation of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448935","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of EU membership that cause so much frustration in the United Kingdom - so we get a better deal for our country and secure our future. We are confident that the right agreement can be reached.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448935/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:39:09.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448935/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448935/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK voting to leave the EU on UK students' participation in the Erasmus scheme.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","24871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448936","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p>We recently published the Green Paper “Fulfilling our potential: Teaching Excellence, Social Mobility and Student Choice,” which sets out our proposals for delivering the Teaching Excellence Framework and reducing the regulatory burden on the sector. The consultation period closed on 15 January 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Once we have considered the consultation responses, and are in a position to publish our final proposals, we will publish a Regulatory Impact Assessment which will set out the costs of implementation.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448936/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:29:56.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448936/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448936/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Teachers: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate what proportion of the cost of introducing the proposed Teaching Excellence Framework will fall to (a) central government and (b) universities.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","24911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448937","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Department for Business Innovation and Skills does not provide direct funding for British schools and institutes abroad which promote UK higher education and research and the international reputation of the UK. Core funding to some overseas research institutes such as the BASIS institutes sponsored by the British Academy, is provided through the science budget. The Government has protected the science budget in real terms to the end of the Parliament. The allocation for the National Academies for 2016-17 to 2019-20 provides for real terms protection for the British Academy’s BASIS programme, enabling the Academy to continue to provide the BASIS Institutes with substantial block grant support throughout this period.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448937/answer",,,,,,"2016-04-12T14:35:08.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448937/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448937/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to maintain core funding for British schools and institutes abroad which promote UK higher education and research and the international reputation of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","24897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448938","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-04","<p>Under DECC’s £20m CCS Innovation Programme, Net Power LLC, a US company, was awarded a Research and Development grant of £7.5m to demonstrate a British invented low carbon power generation technology. Net Power worked with Goodwin Steel castings, an established UK manufacturer, to manufacture turbine casings for the project.</p><p>Through the International Climate Fund (ICF) the Government has funded capacity building projects in a number of partner countries. In December 2012, the UK committed £60 million from the ICF to trust funds operated by the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank to support developing countries to develop both the technical and institutional knowledge necessary to enable the deployment of CCS technologies. The ICF finance is supporting CCS capacity building through pilot projects, with the aim of demonstrating the technology and reducing the cost of the technology application across the CCS chain.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448938/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T14:50:45.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448938/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448938/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-29","Carbon Capture and Storage: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what funding the Government has provided for carbon capture and storage research and development projects not based in the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","24933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448939","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government has taken steps to help reinvigorate the supply chain by stimulating more investment opportunities in the UK Continental Shelf through a £1.3bn package of tax cutting measures and £20m of new funding for a second round of seismic surveys, announced at the end of January 2016.</p><p>The government has taken forward the rapid implementation of the Wood Review and the Oil and Gas Fiscal Review, establishing the Oil and Gas Authority, and in recognition of the current economic pressures hitting the industry, has established a cross-government, Ministerial oil support group. This will look at issues such as how to support the supply chain and workers through this difficult period.</p><p>UKTI also continue to work with supply chain companies to access overseas opportunities in countries including Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan and Mexico.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448939/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:55:49.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448939/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448939/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Oil: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what financial assistance is available to UK businesses in the oil industry supply chain who face financial difficulties resulting from the reduction in the price of oil.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","24922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448940","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>Since summer 2015 the Department has been reviewing its business model. By 2020, we want to simplify our structure, become more digital, be cheaper for taxpayers and better for users. As part of this we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint. The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office in St Paul’s Place was formed in light of these plans.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448940/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-10T16:45:19.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448940/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448940/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of the Minister for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise to the Urgent Question of 29 January 2016, Official Report, on Closure of St Paul's Place, BIS Office (Sheffield), if he will publish the business case for the closure of that office.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","24912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448941","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-10","<p>Since summer 2015 the Department has been reviewing its business model. By 2020, we want to simplify our structure, become more digital, be cheaper for taxpayers and better for users. As part of this we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint. The intention to close the BIS Sheffield office in St Paul’s Place was formed in light of these plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448941/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-10T16:23:01.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448941/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448941/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will publish his Department's business case on the closure of his Department's office in Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448942","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p>As part of the Department’s change programme, BIS2020, we anticipate reducing the number of our locations from more than 80 to approximately 7 centres plus a regional footprint. Beyond the announcement made about our Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place on 28 January, we do not yet know exactly which sites will be retained or closed over the course of the Parliament. By 2020 the majority of employees in BIS and its Partner Organisations will continue to be based outside London through a number of centres – such as in Birmingham, Glasgow, and Swindon – as well as a regional footprint for the provision of local services.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448942/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:10:50.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448942/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448942/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Insolvency Service and Skills Funding Agency: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department plans to close the (a) Skills Funding Agency and (b) Insolvency Service in Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448943","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>Government funding for green innovation is provided for private sector led technology R&amp;D through grants, procurement approaches and to a lesser extent equity interventions. Additionally, DECC, Research Councils and InnovateUK are involved in European programmes that can leverage significant funding from the EC while ensuring cross border collaboration.</p><p>Government spent ~£1.3billion on low carbon innovation for the period 2011-15. In addition, the Low Carbon Networks Fund which is funded by network operators is expected to allocate ~£440m over the period 2010-15. See table 1 attached:</p><p>Separately, the British Business Bank has three main programmes for supporting early stage technology investment, including in the clean technology area: the Enterprise Capital Funds targeted at early stage venture capital investment; the UK Innovation Investment Fund (UKIIF) which supports creation of viable investment funds targeting UK high growth technology-based businesses; and the Venture Capital Catalyst Fund, launched in 2013.</p><p>As part of the recent Spending Review, it was announced that the department for Energy &amp; Climate Change will double its innovation program to £500 million over the next five years.</p><p>UK Green Investment Bank plc (GIB) also invests in innovative green projects, though it does so on fully commercial terms and is focused on technologies ready for deployment at full commercial scale and capable of attracting additional investment from mainstream finance providers. Details of all GIB’s investments to date can be found on the company’s website.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448943/answer","Table 1 24956.docx","Table 1 24956.docx","Table 1","Table 1",,"2016-02-08T16:26:36.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448943/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448943/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Environment Protection: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much public sector funding was spent on facilitating higher risk green investment in each of the last five years; and what estimate he has made of the likely spend of this type in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448944","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p>“BIS 2020: What-why-when-how” (September 2015) was one of a series of internal briefings for BIS staff. Staff are briefed on our change programme on a regular basis. The briefings are not formal documents and, as such, we do not publish them.</p><p>The cost of this report to the public purse consists of the hours worked by Civil Servants on its development. These were not recorded at the time of production separately from the authors’ other work.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448944/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T16:26:53.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448944/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448944/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, who authorised the report entitled, BIS 2020, What-why-when-how; and what the cost to the public purse was of that report.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448945","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government’s proposals to amend and repeal provisions in the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013 relating to UK Green Investment Bank plc (GIB) are contained in clause 30 of the Enterprise Bill. The Government has explained the background to these proposals in paragraphs 62 – 73 of our November 2015 policy statement on the future of GIB which can be found on the GIB pages of the GOV.UK website.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448945/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:20:20.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448945/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448945/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which provisions of the Regulatory Reform Act 2013 need to be removed in order to achieve balance sheet reclassification for the purposes of privatisation of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448946","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Details of why the Government believes moving UK Green Investment Bank plc (GIB) into private ownership represents the best way to enable the company to deliver its ambitious green business plan and have a greater impact on green investment while minimising burdens on the UK taxpayer are provided in our November 2015 policy statement on the future of GIB and are further set out in the Government’s response to the Environmental Audit Committee’s report on the future of GIB which was laid in Parliament on 2 February. Both documents can be found on the GIB pages of the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to report to Parliament setting out our plans for a sale of GIB and will provide a further report following completion of a transaction and any subsequent transactions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448946/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:07:28.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448946/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448946/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-29","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what mechanisms he plans to put in place to measure and monitor (a) value for money for the public purse and (b) the effect on the green economy of a privatised Green Investment Bank; and if he will report regularly to the House on those aspects.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448947","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>The Government’s partial ownership of Bradford and Bingley, the Royal Bank of Scotland and Northern Rock as is a temporary measure following the financial crisis and they will be returned to the private sector in due course. The Government believes this is fundamentally different to public sector bodies that receive ongoing funding from the taxpayer.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448947/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T14:15:14.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448947/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448947/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Banks: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons Bradford and Bingley, the Royal Bank of Scotland and Northern Rock as publicly-funded banks are exempted from the public sector exit payments cap in the provisions of the Enterprise Bill.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448948","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-03","<p>The Government has a target that 33% of central government business, by direct spend and through the supply chain, will go to small and medium businesses by 2020.</p><p>We assess progress against the overall target on a regular basis, including an assessment of those companies identified as Small or Medium Sized Enterprises (SMEs). Where companies no longer meet the statutory definition of an SME at the time of assessment, they are no longer counted.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448948/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T12:26:47.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448948/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448948/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-29","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how Government targets for the proportion of business created in supply chains for small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) under public procurement contracts apply to companies subject to mergers, acquisitions or other changes in status that take those companies out of the SME category.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","24874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448949","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-03","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to him on 1 February 2016 to UIN: 24475.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448949/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T12:11:59.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448949/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448949/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-29","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to bring forward a revised procurement policy note for public authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","24872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448950","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has reviewed a number of options when considering the transition from Aspire. Due to commercial confidentiality, the Department is not in a position to give more details of its plans at this stage. HMRC’s ultimate aim is an operating model that has the right mix of technology, processes and skills, delivered in a multi-sourced model.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448950/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:50:50.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448950/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448950/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of functional areas of the existing HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) IT Aspire contract for which any HMRC plan to create a GoCo capability would not require TUPE transfers of staff.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448951","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-05","<p>The core purpose of NS&amp;I remains to raise cost-effective finance for the Government, using an operating framework that balances the interests of savers, taxpayers and the wider financial sector.</p><p> </p><p>An indication of NS&amp;I’s cost effectiveness in raising finance for the Government, as measured by the Value Indicator, is published annually. The Value Indicator is calculated by comparing the total cost of delivering Net Financing and servicing existing customers deposits with how much it would cost the Government to raise funds through the wholesale market via equivalent maturity gilts. Last year £330m was saved.</p><p> </p><p>As an arms-length body, NS&amp;I is responsible for its own brand strategy. In line with government Spend Controls, Cabinet Office approval is required for advertising, marketing and communications spend of £100,000 or above.</p><p> </p><p>NS&amp;I relocated its operations within Glasgow from the Cowglen site to the Capella building in the centre of Glasgow in May 2015. The closure of Cowglen facilitated the move to more modern and cost effective accommodation and released the surplus site for redevelopment for housing, together with a capital receipt for the Exchequer. NS&amp;I’s mail processing and scanning operations previously located at Cowglen, moved to Orbital House in East Kilbride in October 2015. NS&amp;I remains committed to its operations in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448951/answer",,,,,"24877 ; 24878 ; 24885","2016-02-05T13:57:19.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448951/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448951/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","National Savings and Investments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment his Department has made of the costs and benefits to the (a) public purse and (b) Debt Management Office of the Government's ownership of National Savings and Investments.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24884"
