nt made of the economic effect on Glasgow of the decision by National Savings and Investments (NS&I) to close its Cowglen office; and what further plans his Department has for NS&I operations in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448957","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is responsible for the conduct of tax enquiries. Ministers are not informed of the progress of enquiries and play no part in agreeing the amount of tax to be paid by any taxpayer.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448957/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T15:57:18.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448957/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448957/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Google: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the legal advice he received prior to the tax settlement with Google.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","24896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448958","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>Through the Aspire Replacement Programme, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has considered a wide range of risks that could impact the successful replacement of this contract. The Programme is part of the Government Major Projects Portfolio. The governance bodies for the Programme include senior representatives from across HMRC, Cabinet Office and HM Treasury, in addition to key external expertise from industry.</p><p>Due to commercial confidentiality, HMRC is not in a position to give more details of its plans at this stage.</p><p>HMRC has an ongoing two-way dialogue with relevant trades unions about all matters that affect the Department.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448958/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T15:48:22.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448958/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448958/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will publish (a) a risk analysis, (b) an assessment of the planned transfer of staff, (c) the timetable for TUPE transfers and (d) the date of commencement of consultation with relevant trade unions in relation to the replacement of the HMRC IT Aspire contract.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448959","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>At the Public Accounts Committee hearing of 16 March 2015, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) advised that the transition cost for the entire business case will be about £600 million.</p><p> </p><p>The Business Case setting out the options for the replacement of the Aspire contract is currently subject to formal governance processes, and as such HMRC cannot discuss future plans.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448959/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:21:38.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448959/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has made of the cost of (a) the replacement of and (b) planned privatisations within the HMRC IT Aspire contract.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448960","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>In HM Revenue and Customs’ contract with Concentrix there are three Key Performance Indicators. These cover post and telephony expectations, and all three are currently being met. There is also one Quality Performance Indicator, where the most recent indicative result is 95.2% against an expectation of 97%.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448960/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T15:49:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448960/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448960/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether Concentrix has met its targets set in its service level agreement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448961","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>Total Machine Games Duty (MGD) receipts for the years ending 31 March 2015 and 2014 were £562 million and £502 million. Total Amusement Machine Licence Duty receipts for the year ending 31 March 2013 were £151million.</p><p> </p><p>Receipts from fixed odds betting terminals are not separately identified in the figures published in HMRC’s Tax &amp; Duty bulletin. The bulletin can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutyBulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutyBulletins.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448961/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:11:22.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448961/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448961/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Gaming Machines: Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much revenue has accrued to the public purse from Fixed Odds Betting Terminals in each of the last three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","24921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448962","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>On 5 August 2015, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) announced the next step in its plans to transition from the Aspire contract. The Department is seeking to establish a truly world class IT operation that has the right mix of technology, processes and skills in a multi-sourced model to deliver its digital vision – and savings of up to 24 per cent on its £800m annual IT budget by 2020-21.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is making significant progress in preparing for the end of the Aspire IT contract in 2017. In December 2015, three services previously delivered by Capgemini were successfully brought under HMRC’s direct control.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448962/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T15:26:13.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448962/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448962/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how the replacement of the HM Revenue and Customs IT Aspire contract will be conducted; and whether it will be conducted in separate tranches.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448963","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ discussions with its IT partners have taken place on a regular basis since the Aspire contract began in 2004. The Department created the Aspire Replacement Programme in 2013 to manage discussions with its partners, following the Memorandum of Understanding in 2012 which led to the adaption of the Aspire contract.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448963/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:50:03.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448963/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448963/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department's discussions with Capgemini and Fujitsu began on the replacement of the HM Revenue and Customs IT Aspire contract.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448964","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>The company was set up as a not-for-profit and there are no plans to change its status to a profit-making entity.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448964/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:23:21.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448964/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448964/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has assessed for changing the status of HM Revenue and Customs Digital Technology Services to enable it to become profit-making.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","24882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448965","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>I refer the honorable lady to the answer I provided on 23 November to question 17151. <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-11-23/17151/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-11-23/17151/</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448965/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-08T16:08:39.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448965/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-29","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether hon. Members can raise issues relating to Concentrix when using the hotline to HM Revenue and Customs for hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448966","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-03","<p>We value the work of the supported housing sector extremely highly and are working closely with them to ensure they are supported as effectively as possible.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this we have commissioned an evidence review of supported housing.</p><p> </p><p>The results of this research will determine our future policy development and any appropriate exemptions.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448966/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:35:04.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448966/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448966/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-29","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the postponement of the introduction of the one per cent rent reduction for supported housing requires the postponement of the introduction of the local housing allowance cap for residents living in supported housing.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","24901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448967","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Government is on target to deliver access to superfast broadband for 95% of all UK premises - including social housing - by December 2017, and to extend coverage beyond that as far as possible. We do not hold a breakdown of this information by housing tenure centrally, however this investment is benefiting all types of housing, as well as businesses, and we are proud to be delivering on this critical piece of infrastructure as set out in our manifesto.</p><p> </p><p>Currently, superfast broadband is available to almost 90 per cent of homes and businesses in the UK - up from 45 per cent in 2010. Around 5 per cent of UK homes and business are currently experiencing connection speeds below 10 Mbit/s.</p><p> </p><p>Having reduced the proportion of all UK premises with speeds less than 2 Mbit/s substantially from 11% in 2010 to around 1% in December last year, we have now implemented our commitment of having at least 2 Mbit/s per second basic broadband available to all homes and businesses.</p><p>All premises which are not currently scheduled to get an increase in speed to at least this level are eligible for a subsidised satellite broadband service that can deliver speeds of 10Mbps or more.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has also announced the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) which is set at 10 Mbit/s. This new broadband USO will give people the legal right to request an affordable broadband connection, at a reasonable cost threshold, no matter where they live. We will be consulting on these proposals shortly.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448967/answer",,,,,"24932","2016-02-23T10:05:26.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448967/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448967/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-29","Social Rented Housing: Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many residences classified as social housing (a) do not have access to superfast broadband, (b) have connections slower than 10 Mbit/s and (c) have connections slower than 2Mbit/s; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","24945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448968","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Government is on target to deliver access to superfast broadband for 95% of all UK premises - including social housing - by December 2017, and to extend coverage beyond that as far as possible. We do not hold a breakdown of this information by housing tenure centrally, however this investment is benefiting all types of housing, as well as businesses, and we are proud to be delivering on this critical piece of infrastructure as set out in our manifesto.</p><p> </p><p>Currently, superfast broadband is available to almost 90 per cent of homes and businesses in the UK - up from 45 per cent in 2010. Around 5 per cent of UK homes and business are currently experiencing connection speeds below 10 Mbit/s.</p><p> </p><p>Having reduced the proportion of all UK premises with speeds less than 2 Mbit/s substantially from 11% in 2010 to around 1% in December last year, we have now implemented our commitment of having at least 2 Mbit/s per second basic broadband available to all homes and businesses.</p><p>All premises which are not currently scheduled to get an increase in speed to at least this level are eligible for a subsidised satellite broadband service that can deliver speeds of 10Mbps or more.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has also announced the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) which is set at 10 Mbit/s. This new broadband USO will give people the legal right to request an affordable broadband connection, at a reasonable cost threshold, no matter where they live. We will be consulting on these proposals shortly.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448968/answer",,,,,"24945","2016-02-23T10:05:26.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448968/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448968/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-29","Social Rented Housing: Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that social housing tenants who would like superfast broadband can access connections; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","24932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448969","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-03","<p>We value the work of the supported housing sector extremely highly and are working closely with them to ensure they are supported as effectively as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of this, we have commissioned an evidence review of supported housing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The results of this research will determine any appropriate exemptions.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448969/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:34:43.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448969/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448969/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-29","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether residents living in supported housing will be exempt from the local housing allowance cap.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","24910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448970","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Government is working with the National Housing Federation and the sector on the implementation of the voluntary agreement, which will make Right to Buy equivalent discounts available to 1.3 million housing association tenants. Ahead of full implementation, on the 25 November, we launched a pilot scheme with five housing associations, which will inform the design and delivery of the main Voluntary Right to Buy scheme.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448970/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-04T16:21:44.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448970/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448970/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-29","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23606, if he will estimate the proportion of housing association tenants that will become eligible for Right to Buy in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","24873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448971","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-03","<p>Further information is not available.</p><p>We value the work of the supported housing sector extremely highly and are working closely with them to ensure that they are supported as effectively as possible in advance of the policy taking effect.</p><p>As part of this we have commissioned an evidence review of supported housing.</p><p>The results of this research will determine our f appropriate exemptions. We are also providing Local Authorities with £870 million over the course of this parliament to ensure vulnerable people are protected.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448971/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:38:40.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448971/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448971/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-29","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who may no longer be able to remain in supported housing after introduction of the proposed cap on housing benefit at the rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","24865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448972","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-03","<p>This information is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448972/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T17:34:18.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448972/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448972/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-29","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Warrington and (b) Warrington North constituency in supported housing are in receipt of housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","24866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448973","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>I can confirm a response has been sent to the honourable member.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448973/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-09T13:59:22.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448973/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448973/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-29","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he intends to answer the letter to him dated 17 December 2015 with regard to Mr T Opke.","false","Biography information for Sir Gerald Kaufman","Manchester, Gorton","Sir Gerald Kaufman","24939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448974","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-03","<p>On 21 January the Government published its evaluation of the £50 regulations introduced in April 2015. You can find it here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493714/Evaluation_of_Gaming_Machine__Circumstances_of_Use___Amendment__Regulations_2015.pdf</p><p> </p><p>The evaluation indicates that a large proportion of players of FOBTs may now be making a more conscious choice to control their playing behaviour and their stake level. We will now consider the findings of the evaluation before deciding if there is a need for further action.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448974/answer",,,,,"24919","2016-02-03T16:15:50.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448974/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448974/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-29","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on reducing the stake on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","24920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448975","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-03","<p>On 21 January the Government published its evaluation of the £50 regulations introduced in April 2015. You can find it here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493714/Evaluation_of_Gaming_Machine__Circumstances_of_Use___Amendment__Regulations_2015.pdf</p><p> </p><p>The evaluation indicates that a large proportion of players of FOBTs may now be making a more conscious choice to control their playing behaviour and their stake level. We will now consider the findings of the evaluation before deciding if there is a need for further action.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448975/answer",,,,,"24920","2016-02-03T16:15:50.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448975/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448975/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-29","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he next plans a review of gaming machine stakes and prizes.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","24919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448976","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-05","<p>Regardless of the type of target being considered, the UK performs an assessment prior to every UK strike to assess the likelihood of any civilian casualties. This examines the impact of the strike on the surrounding area and whether there are likely to be any civilians present.</p><p>The UK military takes every possible step to avoid civilian casualties.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448976/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-05T13:21:21.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448976/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448976/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps UK forces take to avoid civilian casualties when targeting (a) oil facilities and (b) other infrastructure in Syria.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","24876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448977","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-03","<p>The Ministry of Defence Police (MDP) currently has a number of vacancies within the Force. Where there is a shortfall in numbers at an MDP station the use of overtime working may be authorised in order to cover essential duties. Volunteers to work additional hours are sought in the first instance, but officers may be directed to work additional hours if insufficient volunteers are available.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448977/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T16:37:54.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448977/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448977/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether there is a shortfall in the number of Ministry of Defence Police Officers; and what provision there is for tasking such officers beyond their contracted hours of work.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","24870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448978","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-03","<p>In line with the rest of the police service, Ministry of Defence Police officers may be subject to disciplinary action if they fail to attend for duty when directed to do so. There are no plans to review this policy.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448978/answer",,,,,,"2016-02-03T16:37:13.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448978/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448978/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Ministry of Defence Police: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether Ministry of Defence Police Officers are subject to disciplinary or unsatisfactory performance procedures in the event that they are unable to undertake additional work in excess of contractual hours; and what plans he has to review that policy.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","24868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448979","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-03","<p>Under the Five Power Defence Arrangements, the five powers (Australia, New Zealand, Malaysia, Singapore and the UK) undertook to consult &quot;immediately&quot; in the event or threat of an armed attack on Malaysia or Singapore for the purpose of deciding what measures should be taken jointly or separately in response. There is no specific commitment to intervene militarily.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448979/answer",,,,,"24955","2016-02-03T16:14:22.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448979/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448979/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Military Alliances: South East Asia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the UK's naval obligations are under the Five Powers Agreement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","24952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448980","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-03","<p>The decision to procure the Rolls Royce WR21 was taken in November 2000 by the then Defence Secretary, Geoff Hoon. In announcing the decision, he accepted this decision &quot;presents a greater degree of risk to the programme.&quot;</p><p> </p><p>Following that decision a number of issues with the Type 45 Integrated Electrical Propulsion (IEP) system were identified when the First of Class, HMS Daring was launched in 2006.</p><p> </p><p>From 2006 to the launch of the sixth and final Type 45 in October 2010, the Type 45 Destroyer class had around fifty minor design alterations directly attributable to the development of the Type 45 IEP system identified. The subsequent implementation process for acceptance of these alterations is necessarily rigorous to maintain safety and system design intent. As a result, the majority of Type 45 IEP alterations were implemented after the launch of the last of class.</p><p> </p><p>A report was commissioned in 2011 to examine the reliability of the power and propulsion system in greater detail. This work was re-assessed in 2013 to examine the extent to which the issues identified in the report had been dealt with, (by changes to operating procedures and training) and establish which were not simply the problems associated with a new complex system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 the Government is committed to improving the Type 45's power and propulsion system an ongoing Equipment Improvement Plan is successfully making further alterations to the existing power and propulsion system.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last two years, Type 45 Destroyers have been routinely deployed to the Gulf to maintain a destroyer presence in the region, including HMS Defender's support to US Carrier operations against Daesh.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448980/answer",,,,,"24954","2016-02-03T16:59:28.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448980/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448980/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-29","Type 45 Destroyers: Engines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what alterations were made to the pulsion system of the Type 45 destroyer between the launch of the first and the sixth such destroyers.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","24953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448981","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-03","<p>The decision to procure the Rolls Royce WR21 was taken in November 2000 by the then Defence Secretary, Geoff Hoon. In announcing the decision, he accepted this decision &quot;presents a greater degree of risk to the programme.&quot;</p><p> </p><p>Following that decision a number of issues with the Type 45 Integrated Electrical Propulsion (IEP) system were identified when the First of Class, HMS Daring was launched in 2006.</p><p> </p><p>From 2006 to the launch of the sixth and final Type 45 in October 2010, the Type 45 Destroyer class had around fifty minor design alterations directly attributable to the development of the Type 45 IEP system identified. The subsequent implementation process for acceptance of these alterations is necessarily rigorous to maintain safety and system design intent. As a result, the majority of Type 45 IEP alterations were implemented after the launch of the last of class.</p><p> </p><p>A report was commissioned in 2011 to examine the reliability of the power and propulsion system in greater detail. This work was re-assessed in 2013 to examine the extent to which the issues identified in the report had been dealt with, (by changes to operating procedures and training) and establish which were not simply the problems associated with a new complex system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 the Government is committed to improving the Type 45's power and propulsion system an ongoing Equipment Improvement Plan is successfully making further alterations to the existing power and propulsion system.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last two years, Type 45 Destroyers have been routinely deployed to the Gulf to maintain a destroyer presence in the region, including HMS Defender's support to US Carrier operations against Daesh.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448981/answer",,,,,"